WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.004
INT: Today's date is
January 25th, 1996.

00:00:05.004 --> 00:00:09.542
The survivor is Celina
Biniaz, maiden named Karp.

00:00:09.542 --> 00:00:11.578
The interviewer
is Carol Stulberg.

00:00:11.578 --> 00:00:14.347
We are in Camarillo,
California in the United

00:00:14.347 --> 00:00:15.548
States of America.

00:00:15.548 --> 00:00:17.183
The language will be English.

00:00:20.286 --> 00:00:23.990
I'm Carol Stulberg,
S-T-U-L-B-E-R-G.

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:26.326
And I have the privilege
of interviewing Mrs.

00:00:26.326 --> 00:00:31.464
Celina Biniaz on January the
25th, 1996, in Camarillo,

00:00:31.464 --> 00:00:34.100
California, in the
United States of America.

00:00:39.239 --> 00:00:41.708
This is January the 25th, 1996.

00:00:41.708 --> 00:00:45.845
We're in Camarillo, California
with Mrs. Celina Biniaz.

00:00:45.845 --> 00:00:49.315
Mrs. Biniaz, can you please
spell your name for us?

00:00:49.315 --> 00:00:52.018
CB: Well, the first
name is C-E-L-I-N-A.

00:00:52.018 --> 00:00:57.457
My last name is B like
in boy, I-N-I-A-Z.

00:00:57.457 --> 00:00:59.526
INT: And what was
your name at birth?

00:00:59.526 --> 00:01:03.263
CB: Karp, Celina Karp, K-A-R-P.

00:01:03.263 --> 00:01:04.731
INT: And where were you born?

00:01:04.731 --> 00:01:06.933
CB: I was born in
Krakow, Poland.

00:01:06.933 --> 00:01:08.401
INT: And when were you born?

00:01:08.401 --> 00:01:11.404
CB: On the 28th of May, 1931.

00:01:11.404 --> 00:01:13.072
INT: So how old are you today?

00:01:13.072 --> 00:01:13.573
CB: 64.

00:01:16.075 --> 00:01:18.912
INT: What were the
names of your parents?

00:01:18.912 --> 00:01:24.851
CB: In Poland, it was Ignatzi
Karp and Felicia Karp.

00:01:24.851 --> 00:01:27.086
INT: And did you have
any brothers or sisters?

00:01:27.086 --> 00:01:27.887
CB: No, I did not.

00:01:27.887 --> 00:01:29.656
I was an only child.

00:01:29.656 --> 00:01:31.724
INT: What was your
father's occupation?

00:01:31.724 --> 00:01:33.393
CB: My father was an accountant.

00:01:33.393 --> 00:01:34.927
INT: Did your
mother work as well?

00:01:34.927 --> 00:01:38.097
CB: She was also an accountant.

00:01:38.097 --> 00:01:41.868
INT: Tell us, please, what your
earliest memories of childhood

00:01:41.868 --> 00:01:44.504
in Krakow were like.

00:01:44.504 --> 00:01:48.241
CB: I had a very
nice, happy childhood.

00:01:48.241 --> 00:01:53.012
Lived sort of a middle
class existence.

00:01:53.012 --> 00:01:54.414
My parents both
worked-- my mother

00:01:54.414 --> 00:01:59.685
was a professional person,
so we had a governess who

00:01:59.685 --> 00:02:01.487
took care of me.

00:02:01.487 --> 00:02:04.657
It was important to be--

00:02:04.657 --> 00:02:06.692
to behave in a certain way.

00:02:06.692 --> 00:02:08.494
I was always very well
dressed, always wore

00:02:08.494 --> 00:02:14.767
white gloves, even to play
in the sandbox in the park.

00:02:14.767 --> 00:02:18.237
Life was kind of
nice till the war.

00:02:18.237 --> 00:02:19.672
INT: When you were
a child, did you

00:02:19.672 --> 00:02:22.575
have extended family members
living around you-- uncles

00:02:22.575 --> 00:02:23.776
or aunts or grandparents?

00:02:23.776 --> 00:02:24.844
CB: Only an aunt.

00:02:24.844 --> 00:02:29.382
My mother's younger
sister lived with us.

00:02:29.382 --> 00:02:30.950
She was an artist.

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:35.188
She painted-- did lots of
interesting embroidery.

00:02:35.188 --> 00:02:36.355
INT: What was her name?

00:02:36.355 --> 00:02:38.491
CB: Gucia.

00:02:38.491 --> 00:02:40.593
INT: Her last name?

00:02:40.593 --> 00:02:41.794
CB: Wittenburg.

00:02:41.794 --> 00:02:46.799
It was my mother's middle
name-- maiden name.

00:02:46.933 --> 00:02:49.735
INT: What was your
religious background like?

00:02:49.735 --> 00:02:51.270
CB: I would say that
it would compare

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:54.740
to the conservative Judaism
in the United States.

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:59.178
We weren't really
orthodox, that orthodox.

00:02:59.178 --> 00:03:00.646
But then, I think,
in Poland, there

00:03:00.646 --> 00:03:03.583
were no divisions in Judaism.

00:03:03.583 --> 00:03:06.018
There was just one religion.

00:03:06.018 --> 00:03:08.521
INT: Did you live in a Jewish
neighborhood, or was it mixed?

00:03:08.521 --> 00:03:09.722
CB: It was very mixed.

00:03:09.722 --> 00:03:12.458
I would say it was
predominantly non-Jewish.

00:03:12.458 --> 00:03:16.095
You know, there were some
Jewish families in the building,

00:03:16.095 --> 00:03:20.099
but I would say that, if I
had to give it a percentage,

00:03:20.099 --> 00:03:26.138
I would say 75% non-Jewish,
maybe 25% Jewish.

00:03:26.138 --> 00:03:28.808
INT: Did you have friends
that were non-Jewish as well

00:03:28.808 --> 00:03:29.608
as Jewish?

00:03:29.608 --> 00:03:31.143
CB: Yes, of course.

00:03:31.143 --> 00:03:33.446
I went to a public school.

00:03:33.446 --> 00:03:36.682
And in the public school,
we were all mixed.

00:03:36.682 --> 00:03:39.085
INT: What do you remember
about public school?

00:03:39.085 --> 00:03:41.253
CB: Well, I only
went to two grades.

00:03:41.253 --> 00:03:47.727
So what I remember is mostly
first grade and second grade.

00:03:47.727 --> 00:03:50.296
I remember my first
grade teacher's name.

00:03:50.296 --> 00:03:56.202
And it was Mrs. Jablonska,
which meant apple.

00:03:56.202 --> 00:03:58.270
INT: What do you
remember about school?

00:03:58.270 --> 00:03:59.972
CB: I enjoyed it tremendously.

00:03:59.972 --> 00:04:02.675
I loved learning.

00:04:02.675 --> 00:04:06.846
I remember saying to my mother,
I will never learn how to read.

00:04:06.846 --> 00:04:08.714
But I did.

00:04:08.714 --> 00:04:11.550
And I-- I did enjoy
reading tremendously.

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:15.888
In Poland, the
libraries were not free,

00:04:15.888 --> 00:04:19.625
and you had to pay for
checking out books.

00:04:19.625 --> 00:04:21.794
And we used to do
this continually.

00:04:21.794 --> 00:04:24.196
I enjoyed that very much.

00:04:24.196 --> 00:04:26.966
INT: Did you also have books
and magazines or newspapers

00:04:26.966 --> 00:04:27.700
at home?

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:29.068
CB: I had a lot of books.

00:04:29.068 --> 00:04:30.736
That was my favorite gift.

00:04:30.736 --> 00:04:35.774
And everybody knew that I
enjoyed getting books as gifts.

00:04:35.774 --> 00:04:37.877
INT: What books do you
remember reading as a child?

00:04:37.877 --> 00:04:40.846
CB: Oh, I remember
Heidi by Johanna Spyri.

00:04:40.846 --> 00:04:45.351
And I think that stands
out very much in my mind,

00:04:45.351 --> 00:04:47.987
because I kind of
wished I had been Heidi

00:04:47.987 --> 00:04:50.756
and had that experience.

00:04:50.756 --> 00:04:56.695
I remember reading
James Fenimore Cooper,

00:04:56.695 --> 00:04:59.365
you know, The Last
of the Mohicans.

00:04:59.365 --> 00:05:04.303
I couldn't imagine what it was
like to be a Native American,

00:05:04.303 --> 00:05:07.339
or an Indian in those days.

00:05:07.339 --> 00:05:11.777
Adventures, Western stories,
and things like that.

00:05:11.777 --> 00:05:15.848
INT: Did you ever experience
any anti-Semitism?

00:05:15.848 --> 00:05:18.550
Do you remember anything
about anti-Semitism?

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:21.854
CB: Well, I remember
particularly,

00:05:21.854 --> 00:05:24.623
at the beginning-- you
know, just prior to the war,

00:05:24.623 --> 00:05:27.660
and at the beginning
of the war, there

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:32.898
was a heightened feeling of
something is going to happen.

00:05:32.898 --> 00:05:38.003
And people used to congregate in
the courtyard of the apartment

00:05:38.003 --> 00:05:41.640
building and talk
about war, and feeling

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.111
that if something-- if
things were going to happen,

00:05:46.111 --> 00:05:48.547
things weren't going to
be so good for the Jews.

00:05:48.547 --> 00:05:50.516
But as a child, no.

00:05:50.516 --> 00:05:53.051
I don't think that I
felt any anti-Semitism.

00:05:53.051 --> 00:05:56.522
I really wouldn't have
known what that was.

00:05:56.522 --> 00:05:57.890
INT: Do you remember
your parents

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.192
speaking about imminent war?

00:06:00.192 --> 00:06:03.362
CB: I remember everybody
talking, congregating,

00:06:03.362 --> 00:06:05.097
and-- and speaking about it.

00:06:05.097 --> 00:06:10.836
And there was a feeling
of not understanding

00:06:10.836 --> 00:06:15.207
what was happening, but feeling
that something was ominous,

00:06:15.207 --> 00:06:17.042
because everybody was concerned.

00:06:17.042 --> 00:06:19.545
You know, the older people
were concerned and talked

00:06:19.545 --> 00:06:24.016
in hushed tones, and listened
to the foreign broadcasts

00:06:24.016 --> 00:06:28.287
on the Telefunken radio--

00:06:28.287 --> 00:06:30.989
on the shortwave.

00:06:30.989 --> 00:06:32.391
INT: What do you
remember thinking

00:06:32.391 --> 00:06:34.026
about that when you heard it?

00:06:36.662 --> 00:06:39.398
CB: Oh, I-- it just--

00:06:39.398 --> 00:06:40.365
a fear.

00:06:40.365 --> 00:06:42.734
I think it was just
a general fear,

00:06:42.734 --> 00:06:45.637
and is-- was our
life going to change?

00:06:45.637 --> 00:06:47.105
That sort of thing.

00:06:47.105 --> 00:06:50.776
And-- and a feeling of--

00:06:50.776 --> 00:06:52.177
we couldn't do certain things.

00:06:52.177 --> 00:06:54.413
And then when war broke
out, of course, right away,

00:06:54.413 --> 00:06:58.317
the schools were closed, and
so our lives really changed.

00:06:58.317 --> 00:07:01.219
INT: Well, what do
you remember as being

00:07:01.219 --> 00:07:07.693
the first signs of trouble
that influenced you as a child?

00:07:07.693 --> 00:07:12.497
CB: Well, I think as soon
as-- as soon as war broke out,

00:07:12.497 --> 00:07:15.133
you know, and we heard--

00:07:15.133 --> 00:07:17.936
well, bombs started falling--

00:07:17.936 --> 00:07:20.305
there were like three,
I think, fell in Krakow

00:07:20.305 --> 00:07:22.741
on the radio station.

00:07:22.741 --> 00:07:25.944
I had just received,
just prior to that,

00:07:25.944 --> 00:07:28.747
a puppy, which was wonderful.

00:07:28.747 --> 00:07:32.584
My-- my aunt bought it for me.

00:07:32.584 --> 00:07:35.020
It was a little
spitz, white spitz.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:37.189
And one of the
first things that I

00:07:37.189 --> 00:07:42.594
had to part with,
painfully, was to give up

00:07:42.594 --> 00:07:46.031
my dog to a shelter, because
my parents felt that,

00:07:46.031 --> 00:07:48.900
couldn't take care of it
with the war approaching.

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:53.071
And I distinctly remember
having to take him to a shelter.

00:07:53.071 --> 00:07:54.639
And that was painful,
because I didn't

00:07:54.639 --> 00:07:55.740
understand why, you know--

00:07:55.740 --> 00:08:02.080
I was only about eight
years old at the time.

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:06.151
INT: So in September of 1939,
when the war started in Poland,

00:08:06.151 --> 00:08:08.920
what do you remember exactly?

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:13.792
CB: I remember people panicking.

00:08:13.792 --> 00:08:15.760
There was a general fear.

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:18.897
I remember that the
neighbors that discussed

00:08:18.897 --> 00:08:23.034
the impending problems
in the courtyard

00:08:23.034 --> 00:08:25.604
on the 2nd of September--

00:08:25.604 --> 00:08:27.839
I mean, war started
on the 1st September--

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:31.076
on the 2nd of September,
appeared with armbands sporting

00:08:31.076 --> 00:08:32.577
swastikas.

00:08:32.577 --> 00:08:35.647
They turned out to have
been fifth columnists.

00:08:35.647 --> 00:08:40.585
So it was really kind
of an incredible feeling

00:08:40.585 --> 00:08:45.991
to realize that you've
been trusting people and--

00:08:45.991 --> 00:08:50.095
an telling them your
feelings and your attitudes,

00:08:50.095 --> 00:08:54.366
and they were
sympathizers of the Nazis,

00:08:54.366 --> 00:08:57.235
or of the Germans at
the time, you know.

00:08:57.235 --> 00:09:00.639
I don't think we really
fully realized what Nazism

00:09:00.639 --> 00:09:03.642
was till it hit us later.

00:09:03.642 --> 00:09:08.313
At that time, we just talked
about Germany invading Poland.

00:09:08.313 --> 00:09:10.982
INT: Well, how did your life
change when the war started?

00:09:10.982 --> 00:09:13.718
CB: Well, as I say, I
lost my dog right away.

00:09:13.718 --> 00:09:19.424
School closed, so we were
not allowed to go to school.

00:09:19.424 --> 00:09:21.626
We were sent-- for
a very short time,

00:09:21.626 --> 00:09:25.597
some of the Jewish families
organized a Jewish school,

00:09:25.597 --> 00:09:30.135
and we were sent
there for a few--

00:09:30.135 --> 00:09:32.404
just a few weeks, really.

00:09:32.404 --> 00:09:37.375
And my father, of
course, left right away.

00:09:37.375 --> 00:09:40.612
I mean, all the men, as
soon as war broke out,

00:09:40.612 --> 00:09:45.984
all the men went east, you
know, on a long march, running--

00:09:45.984 --> 00:09:48.086
sort of running away.

00:09:48.086 --> 00:09:49.554
So we were just left--

00:09:49.554 --> 00:09:54.893
all the women were left
in-- in the building.

00:09:54.893 --> 00:09:56.661
Then my father came
back, fortunately.

00:09:56.661 --> 00:09:58.830
But there was this
incredible fear, you know,

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:01.466
not knowing what was
happening to my father.

00:10:01.466 --> 00:10:03.334
And I could sense
that, I could feel it,

00:10:03.334 --> 00:10:04.869
I could see it in my mother.

00:10:08.106 --> 00:10:10.008
That was the beginning of it.

00:10:10.008 --> 00:10:13.878
It was just kind of a
totally unsettled life.

00:10:13.878 --> 00:10:19.117
And by the time the winter
came, my father was back--

00:10:19.117 --> 00:10:22.387
after a long walk,
you know, back.

00:10:22.387 --> 00:10:25.557
Then when the winter came,
right away, we were told to,

00:10:25.557 --> 00:10:29.160
you know, we were told to
go out and shovel snow,

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:32.697
and do all kinds of menial
tasks for the Germans.

00:10:32.697 --> 00:10:36.334
Life changed
completely, right away.

00:10:36.334 --> 00:10:39.504
My parents-- we knew that
we were going to be-- there

00:10:39.504 --> 00:10:43.608
were rumors that we were going
to be resettled into a ghetto.

00:10:43.608 --> 00:10:48.947
So my parents got rid of their
nice furniture and silver

00:10:48.947 --> 00:10:51.149
and china and all
of these things,

00:10:51.149 --> 00:10:54.852
sold them to the various
non-Jewish neighbors.

00:10:54.852 --> 00:10:57.055
And I think that-- my mother--

00:10:57.055 --> 00:10:58.990
I think it hurt my
mother terribly,

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:02.460
because she liked those things.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:03.828
She was proud of them.

00:11:03.828 --> 00:11:06.164
They were her trousseau.

00:11:06.164 --> 00:11:09.400
It had taken them a while
to accumulate these things,

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:11.602
you know.

00:11:11.602 --> 00:11:14.539
And it just-- life just
changed, completely, you know.

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:15.973
You lost your sense--

00:11:15.973 --> 00:11:19.143
not that you ever had a
tremendous sense of security,

00:11:19.143 --> 00:11:20.945
but as a child, I did.

00:11:20.945 --> 00:11:24.315
And at that point, I no longer
had that sense of security.

00:11:24.315 --> 00:11:27.552
It was totally replaced by the
beginnings of fear, you know.

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:36.294
INT: So what happened when you
were told to leave your homes?

00:11:36.294 --> 00:11:37.261
CB: I remember my--

00:11:37.261 --> 00:11:38.663
my father worked for a--

00:11:38.663 --> 00:11:43.267
he was an accountant in a
shirt factory named HoGo.

00:11:43.267 --> 00:11:47.305
I think, the initials stood
for Horowitz and Goldfarb,

00:11:47.305 --> 00:11:48.406
or something like that.

00:11:48.406 --> 00:11:52.043
But it was sort of
analogous to Arrow

00:11:52.043 --> 00:11:55.580
factory, Arrow Shirt,
a Manhattan, here.

00:11:55.580 --> 00:12:00.084
And he got one of
the maintenance

00:12:00.084 --> 00:12:02.186
men there to come
with a push cart--

00:12:02.186 --> 00:12:05.823
you know that they used to
carry the shirts from one

00:12:05.823 --> 00:12:07.124
place to another.

00:12:07.124 --> 00:12:10.194
And we loaded up some of
our personal belongings,

00:12:10.194 --> 00:12:11.095
and we moved--

00:12:11.095 --> 00:12:12.196
I mean, we didn't--

00:12:12.196 --> 00:12:16.200
a few sticks of furniture,
like mattresses and beds.

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:17.235
And we moved.

00:12:17.235 --> 00:12:18.569
INT: What did you take with you?

00:12:18.569 --> 00:12:20.404
Do you remember?

00:12:20.404 --> 00:12:22.607
CB: Books, probably.

00:12:22.607 --> 00:12:24.242
And maybe some dolls.

00:12:24.242 --> 00:12:27.578
I was very fond of dolls.

00:12:27.578 --> 00:12:28.779
INT: Where did you move to?

00:12:28.779 --> 00:12:31.782
CB: We moved to--
well, they moved us--

00:12:31.782 --> 00:12:33.484
the ghetto then became--

00:12:33.484 --> 00:12:38.956
[PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS]
they moved us into what

00:12:38.956 --> 00:12:43.060
used to be the Jewish
section of town.

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:45.363
And then, actually,
they moved us twice.

00:12:45.363 --> 00:12:48.733
You know, the ghetto
kept shrinking.

00:12:48.733 --> 00:12:52.536
So at first, it was much larger,
and then it shrank some more

00:12:52.536 --> 00:12:53.571
and shrank some more.

00:12:53.571 --> 00:12:57.208
And then they started
breaking us up.

00:12:57.208 --> 00:12:58.709
You know, they--
at first, we didn't

00:12:58.709 --> 00:13:01.445
have any walls
around the ghetto,

00:13:01.445 --> 00:13:05.082
but then they started putting
up a wall around the ghetto,

00:13:05.082 --> 00:13:09.887
and they even bricked
in windows and doors,

00:13:09.887 --> 00:13:12.256
you know, of buildings
facing towards the outside

00:13:12.256 --> 00:13:14.225
of the ghetto.

00:13:14.225 --> 00:13:16.594
We, at first, lived in one
of those buildings that

00:13:16.594 --> 00:13:18.496
faced to the outside
of the ghetto--

00:13:18.496 --> 00:13:21.332
so we could see some of
the trees and things.

00:13:21.332 --> 00:13:23.434
But then they moved
us out of that house,

00:13:23.434 --> 00:13:26.170
because that house
then became part

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:29.373
of the outside of the
ghetto, into more inner--

00:13:29.373 --> 00:13:31.642
say, I think we moved
twice, two or three

00:13:31.642 --> 00:13:34.578
times within the ghetto--

00:13:34.578 --> 00:13:38.315
each time to a
smaller accommodation.

00:13:38.315 --> 00:13:41.085
Each time to share
with more people.

00:13:41.085 --> 00:13:43.287
In other words, you
would have one room,

00:13:43.287 --> 00:13:46.257
and there would be another
family in another room,

00:13:46.257 --> 00:13:49.493
and everybody would be sharing
the kitchen and the hallway

00:13:49.493 --> 00:13:54.765
and the bathrooms.

00:13:54.765 --> 00:13:59.270
Life just became totally
different, you know.

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:02.139
INT: What about food and money?

00:14:02.139 --> 00:14:04.174
How did you come about that?

00:14:04.174 --> 00:14:06.076
CB: Well, we still had--

00:14:06.076 --> 00:14:08.846
well, right away,
as I remember, they

00:14:08.846 --> 00:14:11.348
closed all the bank
accounts, you know,

00:14:11.348 --> 00:14:13.317
Jewish bank accounts
were closed.

00:14:13.317 --> 00:14:16.186
So my parents couldn't
withdraw any money.

00:14:16.186 --> 00:14:19.690
But I'm sure that knowing
the war was coming,

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:23.827
I think everybody sort of put
some money away, and some.

00:14:23.827 --> 00:14:26.096
And I think they sold
a few valuables things.

00:14:26.096 --> 00:14:28.565
I mean, they got some money
for the furniture, and--

00:14:28.565 --> 00:14:29.366
I assume.

00:14:29.366 --> 00:14:31.568
You know, I mean, I didn't
question them at the time.

00:14:31.568 --> 00:14:34.104
But now in retrospect,
I would imagine

00:14:34.104 --> 00:14:36.373
that that's where
the money came from

00:14:36.373 --> 00:14:41.445
and that that's how we
paid for food, you know?

00:14:41.445 --> 00:14:47.117
I mean-- [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS]
Jews tend to be survivors.

00:14:49.887 --> 00:14:52.723
INT: What else do you
remember about the ghetto?

00:14:52.723 --> 00:14:56.326
CB: Well, I remember-- you
know, as a child in the ghetto,

00:14:56.326 --> 00:14:58.829
at first, it was not--

00:14:58.829 --> 00:15:01.765
for a child, we were
then squished together

00:15:01.765 --> 00:15:04.301
in a tight place, but there
were lots of other children.

00:15:04.301 --> 00:15:07.538
So in a sense, there
was more time to play.

00:15:07.538 --> 00:15:10.707
We didn't have school, so
there was more time to play,

00:15:10.707 --> 00:15:15.546
more time to visit
with other people.

00:15:15.546 --> 00:15:17.381
At first, it wasn't
so bad, you know?

00:15:17.381 --> 00:15:19.383
I mean, for a child.

00:15:19.383 --> 00:15:22.252
For the grown ups, it
must have been terrible.

00:15:22.252 --> 00:15:26.690
You know, when I think about
it, now that I'm a parent,

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:29.193
it must have been hard.

00:15:29.193 --> 00:15:30.861
INT: Did your parents
work at that time?

00:15:30.861 --> 00:15:31.595
CB: Yes, they did.

00:15:31.595 --> 00:15:33.130
They continued working.

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:36.300
Both my mother then,
at that point, joined--

00:15:36.300 --> 00:15:45.142
the HoGo factory was taken over,
was given to a person named

00:15:45.142 --> 00:15:46.910
Madritsch.

00:15:46.910 --> 00:15:51.648
And it became slowly
turned from making shirts

00:15:51.648 --> 00:15:56.253
into making army uniforms
for the Wehrmacht.

00:15:56.253 --> 00:15:59.723
It's sort of a parallel
to Schindler making--

00:15:59.723 --> 00:16:03.860
you know, enameled
pots and pans,

00:16:03.860 --> 00:16:07.431
then becoming--
making mess kits.

00:16:07.431 --> 00:16:10.968
Madritsch then took over, and
then my mother and my father

00:16:10.968 --> 00:16:13.003
both worked for
Madritsch in the--

00:16:13.003 --> 00:16:14.171
in the office.

00:16:14.171 --> 00:16:17.975
My father ran the factory,
because he sort of knew it--

00:16:17.975 --> 00:16:22.679
he was, you know, in
terms of accounting

00:16:22.679 --> 00:16:27.451
and being able to predict how to
make money out of it, I guess.

00:16:27.451 --> 00:16:28.852
And my mother
worked in the office

00:16:28.852 --> 00:16:31.455
taking care of the books.

00:16:31.455 --> 00:16:35.025
INT: What did you do during the
day while they were at work?

00:16:35.025 --> 00:16:37.461
CB: Just sort of
hung around, really.

00:16:37.461 --> 00:16:38.595
I was all alone, really.

00:16:38.595 --> 00:16:43.800
They left the ghetto to go to
work, and I was left behind.

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:49.906
Which, I'm sure, must have been
very difficult for my parents.

00:16:49.906 --> 00:16:52.576
And then, as things progressed
and got worse and worse

00:16:52.576 --> 00:16:54.611
in the ghetto--
as they, you know,

00:16:54.611 --> 00:16:58.148
made the ghetto smaller
by transporting people out

00:16:58.148 --> 00:17:00.317
of the ghetto,
and at that point,

00:17:00.317 --> 00:17:02.352
we didn't know where they
were transporting them,

00:17:02.352 --> 00:17:05.255
you know, except someplace.

00:17:05.255 --> 00:17:08.258
As the ghetto got
smaller and smaller,

00:17:08.258 --> 00:17:12.162
it became evident that--

00:17:12.162 --> 00:17:13.296
at least for my parents--

00:17:13.296 --> 00:17:18.602
that the best thing would be for
me to go out with them to work.

00:17:18.602 --> 00:17:24.708
So they were able to,
through knowing somebody,

00:17:24.708 --> 00:17:30.347
to get a blue card for
me, which was a permit--

00:17:30.347 --> 00:17:33.350
a work permit, really,
to go out of the ghetto.

00:17:33.350 --> 00:17:35.085
For a while there, I
worked in the ghetto.

00:17:35.085 --> 00:17:39.890
I worked at a paper cooperative.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:43.193
They only employed
children, really--

00:17:43.193 --> 00:17:46.329
licking envelopes,
making envelopes.

00:17:46.329 --> 00:17:48.632
I also worked at a
brush co-operative

00:17:48.632 --> 00:17:53.236
making brushes, sticking, you
know, the bristles into a brush

00:17:53.236 --> 00:17:54.871
and pulling it with a wire.

00:17:54.871 --> 00:17:58.441
But that was not very
long that I remember.

00:17:58.441 --> 00:18:00.911
My parents were able to get--

00:18:00.911 --> 00:18:05.915
to fake my age, make
it two years older,

00:18:05.915 --> 00:18:09.719
to allow me to go out
of the ghetto with them.

00:18:09.719 --> 00:18:14.357
And got the blue card
for me, and then I

00:18:14.357 --> 00:18:18.595
joined them going to
Madritsch out of the ghetto.

00:18:18.595 --> 00:18:22.332
And I was-- then started
working on a sewing machine.

00:18:22.332 --> 00:18:23.800
INT: What exactly did you do?

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:28.638
CB: Sewed uniforms,
exactly sewed uniforms.

00:18:28.638 --> 00:18:29.939
You know what piece work is?

00:18:29.939 --> 00:18:31.441
That's what I did.

00:18:31.441 --> 00:18:34.678
You know, everybody gets
either a piece of a sleeve

00:18:34.678 --> 00:18:37.580
or a piece of a pocket,
and-- and you work on it.

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:39.315
INT: And how old were
you at this time?

00:18:39.315 --> 00:18:40.216
CB: Well, let me see.

00:18:40.216 --> 00:18:42.652
I must have been nine--

00:18:42.652 --> 00:18:46.022
nine or 10, and they
made me two years older.

00:18:46.022 --> 00:18:50.326
So it would have been, you know,
according to the records, 12.

00:18:50.326 --> 00:18:52.362
INT: But how old were
you really at that time?

00:18:52.362 --> 00:18:53.963
CB: Between nine and 10.

00:18:53.963 --> 00:18:55.498
INT: And what year was that?

00:18:55.498 --> 00:19:01.004
CB: Must have been 1940 or '41,
someplace in between there.

00:19:01.004 --> 00:19:04.674
Probably right about
there, you know.

00:19:04.674 --> 00:19:08.745
I'm not exact on the figures,
because I don't really

00:19:08.745 --> 00:19:11.581
remember the exact times
that the ghetto got

00:19:11.581 --> 00:19:15.218
smaller and smaller, except
that I think in 1943,

00:19:15.218 --> 00:19:20.323
it closed completely, and
we were transported to--

00:19:20.323 --> 00:19:21.825
that was the last selection.

00:19:21.825 --> 00:19:25.261
We were transported to Plaszow,
which became a labor camp.

00:19:25.261 --> 00:19:27.130
At first, it was a labor camp.

00:19:27.130 --> 00:19:30.233
Then it became a
concentration camp.

00:19:30.233 --> 00:19:33.670
INT: So when you say it
was the last selection,

00:19:33.670 --> 00:19:36.573
what do you mean by that?

00:19:36.573 --> 00:19:40.977
CB: What I mean by that is
that, one day they came in,

00:19:40.977 --> 00:19:42.679
and I think--

00:19:42.679 --> 00:19:46.115
I think this is what is shown so
very well in Schindler's List,

00:19:46.115 --> 00:19:47.450
because--

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.553
except that I don't think--

00:19:50.553 --> 00:19:54.090
rightly so, it was not shown
in its complete horror.

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:59.195
Because what really happened
is that the German--

00:19:59.195 --> 00:20:00.697
well, I don't know
whether they were

00:20:00.697 --> 00:20:04.133
SS or soldiers or whoever--

00:20:04.133 --> 00:20:06.903
took some of the children and
absolutely knocked their heads

00:20:06.903 --> 00:20:07.603
on the walls.

00:20:07.603 --> 00:20:10.873
They swung them by the legs
and killed them that way.

00:20:10.873 --> 00:20:12.875
It was a horrible experience.

00:20:12.875 --> 00:20:13.943
INT: Did you witness this?

00:20:13.943 --> 00:20:15.712
CB: I saw it, yes.

00:20:15.712 --> 00:20:17.213
We all saw it, you know.

00:20:17.213 --> 00:20:19.682
INT: What did you think
as a child at that time?

00:20:19.682 --> 00:20:21.884
CB: I was afraid.

00:20:21.884 --> 00:20:23.453
I mean, what did I think?

00:20:23.453 --> 00:20:29.959
The overwhelming emotion that
has probably ruled my life

00:20:29.959 --> 00:20:34.697
has been fear-- fear of
authority and fear in general.

00:20:34.697 --> 00:20:36.699
[BACKGROUND NOISE]

00:20:40.536 --> 00:20:43.406
INT: Let's wait a second until
this helicopter goes away.

00:20:43.406 --> 00:20:45.775
CB: OK.

00:20:45.775 --> 00:20:48.111
It doesn't want to.

00:20:48.111 --> 00:20:50.113
[BACKGROUND NOISE]

00:20:53.783 --> 00:20:57.587
INT: Let's stop for a minute.

00:20:57.587 --> 00:20:59.555
OK, now the helicopter
is gone and we

00:20:59.555 --> 00:21:02.592
can go back to what you were
saying about your feelings

00:21:02.592 --> 00:21:03.392
at that time.

00:21:03.392 --> 00:21:07.463
CB: As I said, you know,
the overwhelming emotion

00:21:07.463 --> 00:21:10.600
that I remember was fear.

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:15.805
You know-- not so much anger,
but kind of a questioning,

00:21:15.805 --> 00:21:18.641
how could anybody do
anything like that?

00:21:18.641 --> 00:21:21.577
I think it was at
the age of 12 that I

00:21:21.577 --> 00:21:25.815
know that I lost my faith in
God, because I knew that no--

00:21:25.815 --> 00:21:30.686
I mean, the Jews believed that
God-- at least the explanation

00:21:30.686 --> 00:21:32.588
was-- that the
reason things were

00:21:32.588 --> 00:21:37.026
happening to the Jews because
of the sins of our forefathers.

00:21:37.026 --> 00:21:41.530
And I simply couldn't
believe that any god would

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:43.532
allow a child to be killed.

00:21:43.532 --> 00:21:48.104
So I had-- I had
my doubts about it,

00:21:48.104 --> 00:21:50.373
and I have not really
resolved them since.

00:21:53.009 --> 00:21:55.244
INT: So after this
incident with the Germans

00:21:55.244 --> 00:21:57.246
killing all these children--

00:21:57.246 --> 00:21:57.747
CB: Babies.

00:21:57.747 --> 00:22:00.583
INT: --what happened
to you next?

00:22:00.583 --> 00:22:03.486
CB: Well, we-- we went--

00:22:03.486 --> 00:22:08.324
we were transported out of
the ghetto and into Plaszow.

00:22:08.324 --> 00:22:09.992
INT: How did you get there?

00:22:09.992 --> 00:22:12.561
CB: I believe they
took us by trucks--

00:22:12.561 --> 00:22:13.295
or we walked.

00:22:13.295 --> 00:22:14.964
I can't even remember.

00:22:14.964 --> 00:22:17.266
We might have walked
directly from the factory.

00:22:17.266 --> 00:22:19.635
I'm not sure.

00:22:19.635 --> 00:22:23.139
Of course, at that point,
everything was left behind.

00:22:23.139 --> 00:22:26.108
The only thing that we had on
were the clothes on our backs,

00:22:26.108 --> 00:22:27.843
you know.

00:22:27.843 --> 00:22:30.146
So no possessions at all.

00:22:30.146 --> 00:22:34.617
We, you know, we lived in
barracks, five to a berth.

00:22:37.319 --> 00:22:38.621
That was it.

00:22:38.621 --> 00:22:40.756
But for a while
there, you know, we

00:22:40.756 --> 00:22:47.296
were able to walk out of the
Plaszow camp and walk about--

00:22:47.296 --> 00:22:52.134
I think the trip took about
90 minutes each way to our--

00:22:52.134 --> 00:22:54.937
to the factory, to
Madritsch factory.

00:22:54.937 --> 00:22:58.908
The factory was
moved really from--

00:22:58.908 --> 00:23:00.476
the factory had been
moved originally,

00:23:00.476 --> 00:23:05.781
I think, from middle
of Krakow to Podgorze,

00:23:05.781 --> 00:23:09.451
which is kind of a little
suburb over the bridge, of the--

00:23:09.451 --> 00:23:12.254
Vistula bridge.

00:23:12.254 --> 00:23:15.124
And Madritsch established
a factory there.

00:23:15.124 --> 00:23:20.796
And we walked from Plaszow
to this factory every day,

00:23:20.796 --> 00:23:21.830
and walked back.

00:23:21.830 --> 00:23:25.067
We were not as fortunate
as the Schindler

00:23:25.067 --> 00:23:29.572
people, who were able to
stay and live at the factory.

00:23:29.572 --> 00:23:33.609
We had to live in the barracks.

00:23:33.609 --> 00:23:37.746
You know that Plaszow, the
camp, was made originally

00:23:37.746 --> 00:23:40.816
on the Jewish cemetery.

00:23:40.816 --> 00:23:43.652
So they crushed the stones.

00:23:43.652 --> 00:23:47.990
So we walked every day over
people's names, you know.

00:23:47.990 --> 00:23:51.460
So that was kind of
humiliating, too--

00:23:51.460 --> 00:23:53.295
especially to
people who had, you

00:23:53.295 --> 00:23:56.365
know, relatives buried
at that cemetery.

00:23:56.365 --> 00:23:58.767
That was the largest
Jewish cemetery in Krakow.

00:24:02.037 --> 00:24:03.906
INT: What else do you
remember about Plaszow?

00:24:03.906 --> 00:24:05.674
What were the living
conditions like there?

00:24:05.674 --> 00:24:08.277
CB: They were pretty primitive.

00:24:08.277 --> 00:24:10.112
I mean, all we had
were the barracks.

00:24:10.112 --> 00:24:13.115
And you know, Poland gets
very, very cold in the winter,

00:24:13.115 --> 00:24:14.216
so we shivered.

00:24:14.216 --> 00:24:19.021
We were expected-- every
morning, early in the morning,

00:24:19.021 --> 00:24:21.690
we were called to
the appelplatz, which

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:27.196
was a counting place where they,
you know, lined us up in fives

00:24:27.196 --> 00:24:29.932
and counted us.

00:24:29.932 --> 00:24:31.767
And we stood there
for a long time,

00:24:31.767 --> 00:24:35.137
and-- you know, if the
count did not jive,

00:24:35.137 --> 00:24:37.372
you had to wait until it
jived before they would

00:24:37.372 --> 00:24:39.174
excuse us to go to our work.

00:24:43.879 --> 00:24:47.883
From the time-- from the time
we started going from the ghetto

00:24:47.883 --> 00:24:49.351
to the--

00:24:49.351 --> 00:24:53.856
to the factory, we
always walked in fives.

00:24:53.856 --> 00:24:55.624
And that sort of became--

00:24:55.624 --> 00:24:58.193
after the war, it was very
difficult to walk alone.

00:24:58.193 --> 00:25:01.063
[LAUGHS] You always looked
on either side of you

00:25:01.063 --> 00:25:03.265
to see whether you had
your teammates with you,

00:25:03.265 --> 00:25:06.902
or your people from your five.

00:25:06.902 --> 00:25:11.874
But for me, that was very
good, because I was a child.

00:25:11.874 --> 00:25:15.611
And though I was tall,
by being able to walk

00:25:15.611 --> 00:25:19.348
amongst other five, I
was not as prominent.

00:25:19.348 --> 00:25:23.018
So that's-- you know-- that
was a security measure for me.

00:25:23.018 --> 00:25:25.120
INT: Were there other
children with you at Plaszow?

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:28.323
CB: At the time, yes, there
were quite a few children still,

00:25:28.323 --> 00:25:30.892
you know, in Plaszow.

00:25:30.892 --> 00:25:34.062
As long as it was a labor camp.

00:25:34.062 --> 00:25:38.800
But the one day, they had
a selection in Plaszow,

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:40.902
and they took a lot
of the children away.

00:25:40.902 --> 00:25:45.340
And some of the children hid
themselves in the latrines.

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:47.776
You know, that's
how they survived.

00:25:47.776 --> 00:25:51.580
I remember, we smuggled a couple
children out in our fives,

00:25:51.580 --> 00:25:57.085
you know, in sacks between
us, out of the camp.

00:25:57.085 --> 00:26:01.923
And then, once the camp
became a concentration camp,

00:26:01.923 --> 00:26:03.859
we no longer could go out.

00:26:03.859 --> 00:26:07.929
And so Madritsch established
his factory in the camp,

00:26:07.929 --> 00:26:13.368
in some barracks, away
from the living quarters.

00:26:13.368 --> 00:26:15.937
At that point, of
course, in Plaszow

00:26:15.937 --> 00:26:20.375
already, one other thing that
happened when the ghetto closed

00:26:20.375 --> 00:26:22.144
is that my father,
of course, then

00:26:22.144 --> 00:26:25.380
became part of the men's
section, and my mother

00:26:25.380 --> 00:26:27.883
and I became part of
the women's section.

00:26:27.883 --> 00:26:33.221
And we weren't reunited again
until after the war, you know.

00:26:33.221 --> 00:26:35.490
Except at work, we saw
each other at work.

00:26:35.490 --> 00:26:41.029
But in terms of living
areas, the men were the men,

00:26:41.029 --> 00:26:43.999
and the women were the women.

00:26:43.999 --> 00:26:48.436
INT: Did you have any
outstanding memories

00:26:48.436 --> 00:26:50.705
that you'd like to share
with us about any experiences

00:26:50.705 --> 00:26:53.775
at Plaszow that happened to you?

00:26:53.775 --> 00:26:59.548
CB: Well, I witnessed a
couple hangings of young boys.

00:26:59.548 --> 00:27:02.517
He happened to have sung
a song or something,

00:27:02.517 --> 00:27:05.620
and they, you know,
they hung him for that.

00:27:05.620 --> 00:27:07.389
I witnessed the killing--

00:27:07.389 --> 00:27:11.026
Goeth shooting somebody
right in front of-- you

00:27:11.026 --> 00:27:13.194
know, I mean, I was in
the barrack looking out,

00:27:13.194 --> 00:27:14.596
and I saw him.

00:27:14.596 --> 00:27:21.403
He came-- he was a relative
of [? Hilowitz, ?] who was

00:27:21.403 --> 00:27:24.940
probably the most
prominent kapo--

00:27:24.940 --> 00:27:28.643
Jewish policeman in the camp.

00:27:28.643 --> 00:27:31.479
And he came and shot this guy.

00:27:31.479 --> 00:27:34.115
And the woman-- his wife
ran out of the barrack

00:27:34.115 --> 00:27:36.651
to see what was happening,
and he shot her, too.

00:27:36.651 --> 00:27:38.687
INT: Who did the shooting?

00:27:38.687 --> 00:27:39.387
CB: Goeth did.

00:27:39.387 --> 00:27:40.221
INT: Amon Goeth?

00:27:40.221 --> 00:27:40.722
CB: Amon Goeth, yes.

00:27:40.722 --> 00:27:42.057
INT: The commandant of the camp.

00:27:42.057 --> 00:27:43.358
CB: The commandant.

00:27:43.358 --> 00:27:46.795
So that's one outstanding
memory that I have.

00:27:46.795 --> 00:27:48.730
Having to watch somebody being--

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:51.666
the hanging was terrible.

00:27:51.666 --> 00:27:53.968
Being made to watch
beatings of women,

00:27:53.968 --> 00:27:57.038
you know, that was horrible.

00:27:57.038 --> 00:27:59.541
And always being afraid
that we might be singled out

00:27:59.541 --> 00:28:02.110
for something like that, too.

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:06.081
The fear-- the fear
was just incredible.

00:28:06.081 --> 00:28:07.849
INT: I'm going to
stop you right there.

00:28:07.849 --> 00:28:09.551
We're going to change
the tape, and we'll

00:28:09.551 --> 00:28:12.787
start off with a new tape in.

00:28:13.555 --> 00:28:17.158
INT: 25th, 1996, in
Camarillo, California.

00:28:17.158 --> 00:28:21.029
Mrs. Biniaz, you were telling
us about your constant fear

00:28:21.029 --> 00:28:24.532
at Plaszow, and your
experiences with Amon

00:28:24.532 --> 00:28:27.235
Goeth, the commandant.

00:28:27.235 --> 00:28:29.404
Did you see him often there?

00:28:29.404 --> 00:28:30.605
CB: Quite often.

00:28:30.605 --> 00:28:34.576
You know, he took great
pleasure frightening people,

00:28:34.576 --> 00:28:37.579
so he would enjoy walking
through the camp with his two

00:28:37.579 --> 00:28:40.782
huge Great Danes, and he--

00:28:40.782 --> 00:28:47.322
he got enormous pleasure out
of putting fear into people.

00:28:47.322 --> 00:28:52.026
There was just-- he
was a very evil man.

00:28:52.026 --> 00:28:54.028
I also distinctly
remember one day,

00:28:54.028 --> 00:28:59.133
he came to Madritsch, spoke to
my father, and all of a sudden

00:28:59.133 --> 00:29:02.971
we saw my father walking
with him down the road.

00:29:02.971 --> 00:29:06.708
Well, it was incredible
fear, because we

00:29:06.708 --> 00:29:10.144
didn't know that my father
was going to return, you know?

00:29:10.144 --> 00:29:11.879
But he did-- he did come back.

00:29:11.879 --> 00:29:14.949
I don't know what
it was all about.

00:29:14.949 --> 00:29:16.784
But you see, Goeth was--

00:29:16.784 --> 00:29:19.654
Madritsch was
friendly with Goeth,

00:29:19.654 --> 00:29:22.056
just as Schindler was
friendly with Goeth,

00:29:22.056 --> 00:29:25.126
in a sense that
they were supplying

00:29:25.126 --> 00:29:28.730
Goeth with all kinds
of goodies, you know.

00:29:28.730 --> 00:29:32.967
That's how, you know,
the bribery worked.

00:29:32.967 --> 00:29:35.837
And so we had a certain
amount of protection,

00:29:35.837 --> 00:29:38.506
as long as we worked
for Madritsch.

00:29:38.506 --> 00:29:40.575
Madritsch was a
wonderful person--

00:29:40.575 --> 00:29:44.479
he and his companion,
Mr. Titsch.

00:29:44.479 --> 00:29:46.013
They were really classy--

00:29:46.013 --> 00:29:49.250
two people who somehow
just got caught.

00:29:49.250 --> 00:29:51.386
You know, there were a lot
of Germans and Austrians

00:29:51.386 --> 00:29:55.189
who were caught
in the situation,

00:29:55.189 --> 00:29:58.493
not of their doing, really, and
they did the best they could.

00:29:58.493 --> 00:30:00.762
They did bring in food for us.

00:30:00.762 --> 00:30:04.298
Madritsch brought in loads of--

00:30:04.298 --> 00:30:07.401
loaves of bread for the
people-- for his workers--

00:30:07.401 --> 00:30:09.804
and medications.

00:30:09.804 --> 00:30:11.305
They were very decent people.

00:30:14.075 --> 00:30:15.810
INT: So how long
did you actually

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.812
work at the Madritsch factory?

00:30:17.812 --> 00:30:19.347
CB: I worked at the
Madritsch factory

00:30:19.347 --> 00:30:22.617
till the concentration
camp closed--

00:30:22.617 --> 00:30:24.118
which was, I believe--

00:30:24.118 --> 00:30:27.088
now I have a hard
time remembering

00:30:27.088 --> 00:30:30.858
whether it was September that
the camp actually closed,

00:30:30.858 --> 00:30:35.229
and we were all
shipped to Auschwitz.

00:30:35.229 --> 00:30:40.501
Well, It was at that time that
Schindler came to Madritsch

00:30:40.501 --> 00:30:43.304
and made him a proposition,
and said, you know,

00:30:43.304 --> 00:30:46.841
I'm taking my people
to Czechoslovakia.

00:30:46.841 --> 00:30:50.878
Why don't you reestablish a
factory in Czechoslovakia?

00:30:50.878 --> 00:30:53.180
And Madritsch said he
didn't want to-- he had

00:30:53.180 --> 00:30:55.583
had enough of the whole thing.

00:30:55.583 --> 00:30:57.752
But Schindler said
to him, well then,

00:30:57.752 --> 00:31:01.255
I'm making a list of people
that I'm taking with me.

00:31:01.255 --> 00:31:04.392
And I am-- because
we're friends,

00:31:04.392 --> 00:31:07.695
I want you to give me some
names from your people.

00:31:07.695 --> 00:31:10.231
And that's how we
got on the list--

00:31:10.231 --> 00:31:13.301
on Schindler's list, and
that's how we survived.

00:31:13.301 --> 00:31:16.037
It was really
thanks to Madritsch,

00:31:16.037 --> 00:31:19.573
who was grateful,
really, to my parents

00:31:19.573 --> 00:31:22.977
for having worked so
well for him, you know,

00:31:22.977 --> 00:31:24.412
that he put us on the list.

00:31:24.412 --> 00:31:30.651
He put on quite a few people
from the factory on the list.

00:31:30.651 --> 00:31:32.086
And that's how we got on.

00:31:32.086 --> 00:31:36.157
INT: Do you remember
Madritsch's first name?

00:31:36.157 --> 00:31:38.793
CB: I'm trying to think
of his first name.

00:31:38.793 --> 00:31:42.863
I know that Titsch's
first name was Raymond.

00:31:42.863 --> 00:31:44.698
Madritsch's first name?

00:31:44.698 --> 00:31:47.668
I may think of it, I don't know.

00:31:47.668 --> 00:31:51.872
INT: So when they closed
the concentration camp,

00:31:51.872 --> 00:31:54.275
how did you find out you
were going to Auschwitz?

00:31:54.275 --> 00:31:56.277
Or did you find out you
were going to Auschwitz?

00:31:56.277 --> 00:31:59.046
CB: We found out when we
ended up in Auschwitz.

00:31:59.046 --> 00:32:02.483
We were put on a train--
we thought we were--

00:32:02.483 --> 00:32:09.857
the men were shipped
earlier, and we--

00:32:09.857 --> 00:32:12.660
the women were then
shipped in the cattle cars.

00:32:12.660 --> 00:32:15.529
And it took quite a few days--

00:32:15.529 --> 00:32:16.597
it took some time.

00:32:16.597 --> 00:32:19.266
We didn't really realize
that we were getting--

00:32:19.266 --> 00:32:21.769
going to Auschwitz
till we arrived there

00:32:21.769 --> 00:32:24.738
in the middle of the night,
and they emptied out the cars,

00:32:24.738 --> 00:32:26.540
and we saw where we were.

00:32:26.540 --> 00:32:31.045
And it was a very
frightening experience.

00:32:31.045 --> 00:32:33.547
INT: While you were in the
cars those three days--

00:32:33.547 --> 00:32:36.217
the cattle cars-- what
was that like for you?

00:32:36.217 --> 00:32:38.018
CB: Well, it was hard.

00:32:38.018 --> 00:32:41.455
You know, it was-- we
were all cramped together.

00:32:41.455 --> 00:32:45.626
We had no water,
no food, nothing.

00:32:45.626 --> 00:32:49.263
But I think-- and the fear
of not knowing where we were

00:32:49.263 --> 00:32:50.698
going-- you know,
really, I mean,

00:32:50.698 --> 00:32:52.766
we didn't-- we were being--

00:32:52.766 --> 00:32:54.134
the reason it took so long--

00:32:54.134 --> 00:32:59.340
I mean, Krakow and
Auschwitz are very close.

00:32:59.340 --> 00:33:03.944
It's only like 35 miles, or
no more than 50 miles away.

00:33:03.944 --> 00:33:08.115
But because the Russians
were approaching,

00:33:08.115 --> 00:33:10.851
there were many trains
being shunted over

00:33:10.851 --> 00:33:12.853
to different sidelines--

00:33:12.853 --> 00:33:15.756
styled rails, you know.

00:33:15.756 --> 00:33:16.924
That's why it took--

00:33:16.924 --> 00:33:17.992
it didn't take three days.

00:33:17.992 --> 00:33:19.626
It just took a day
and a half, I think.

00:33:19.626 --> 00:33:23.330
It took us three and a half
days to go from Auschwitz

00:33:23.330 --> 00:33:24.865
to Czechoslovakia.

00:33:24.865 --> 00:33:26.700
That was the long trip.

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:29.570
But we ended up in Auschwitz
in the middle of the night,

00:33:29.570 --> 00:33:32.539
and that was a
horrible experience.

00:33:32.539 --> 00:33:34.675
INT: Describe what you remember.

00:33:34.675 --> 00:33:45.185
CB: Fear, smell, burning
flesh, shouting, orders,

00:33:45.185 --> 00:33:50.190
not knowing which way
to-- music being played.

00:33:50.190 --> 00:33:52.893
Slush, on-- you know-- on--

00:33:52.893 --> 00:33:55.963
the mud on the-- on the road.

00:33:55.963 --> 00:33:59.833
You know, the Germans barking at
us-- get out, get out, get out,

00:33:59.833 --> 00:34:01.935
you know, from the cattle cars.

00:34:01.935 --> 00:34:04.638
Finding ourselves on this--

00:34:04.638 --> 00:34:06.173
and realizing where we were.

00:34:06.173 --> 00:34:10.978
And you know, the fear that
that was the end, you know?

00:34:10.978 --> 00:34:12.813
INT: Were you with your
mother at this time?

00:34:12.813 --> 00:34:13.514
CB: All the time.

00:34:13.514 --> 00:34:15.249
I was with my
mother all the time.

00:34:15.249 --> 00:34:17.684
And of course, the first
place they took us to,

00:34:17.684 --> 00:34:23.891
they walked us into the
sauna, which is the--

00:34:23.891 --> 00:34:27.628
supposedly the delousing
room, or whatever.

00:34:27.628 --> 00:34:29.963
But we, at that
point, already had

00:34:29.963 --> 00:34:31.665
heard what happened
in Auschwitz,

00:34:31.665 --> 00:34:34.968
so when they told us to strip
and take our clothes off,

00:34:34.968 --> 00:34:36.603
and they shaved our
heads and all that,

00:34:36.603 --> 00:34:38.005
and they shoved us into the--

00:34:38.005 --> 00:34:42.743
[PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS]
the shower room, you know,

00:34:42.743 --> 00:34:45.846
we didn't know what
to expect, you know?

00:34:45.846 --> 00:34:47.814
Whether we were going
to have the gas,

00:34:47.814 --> 00:34:50.684
or whether we were going
to have actual water.

00:34:50.684 --> 00:34:53.487
It was a horrible
experience, you know?

00:34:53.487 --> 00:34:55.822
When the water finally
came, it was just like--

00:34:55.822 --> 00:34:58.692
we couldn't believe
it, you know.

00:34:58.692 --> 00:35:00.394
INT: And what
happened after that?

00:35:00.394 --> 00:35:02.029
CB: Well, they gave us clothes.

00:35:02.029 --> 00:35:03.463
I mean, they took
our clothes away

00:35:03.463 --> 00:35:07.134
and they gave us their clothes,
so we no longer had anything

00:35:07.134 --> 00:35:11.571
of our own anymore,
at all, you know.

00:35:11.571 --> 00:35:14.241
And then they took
us to the barracks.

00:35:14.241 --> 00:35:15.742
INT: What were
the barracks like?

00:35:15.742 --> 00:35:16.610
CB: Cold.

00:35:16.610 --> 00:35:17.811
Very cold.

00:35:17.811 --> 00:35:21.381
I mean, Poland gets very cold
starting from October on,

00:35:21.381 --> 00:35:22.115
you know?

00:35:22.115 --> 00:35:24.217
It was very cold.

00:35:24.217 --> 00:35:27.454
And the thing that-- you know,
and they kept pulling us out

00:35:27.454 --> 00:35:29.356
of the barracks every--

00:35:29.356 --> 00:35:31.491
and make us stand in
front, and count us

00:35:31.491 --> 00:35:33.627
and count us, again in fives.

00:35:33.627 --> 00:35:37.297
So we would switch places, you
know, so the person in front

00:35:37.297 --> 00:35:39.966
and the person in the back
wouldn't get so cold, you know.

00:35:39.966 --> 00:35:42.469
We would take turns.

00:35:42.469 --> 00:35:46.206
And of course, food
was very limited.

00:35:46.206 --> 00:35:50.277
So we were hungry, very hungry.

00:35:50.277 --> 00:35:51.845
INT: What was the food like?

00:35:51.845 --> 00:35:56.016
CB: Just a pot of watery soup
and a little piece of bread.

00:35:56.016 --> 00:35:57.717
That was it.

00:35:57.717 --> 00:36:00.654
And the most important thing
was to keep yourself clean,

00:36:00.654 --> 00:36:03.890
because the slightest pimple
on your body, or anything,

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:08.061
would right away make
you go to the wrong side.

00:36:08.061 --> 00:36:10.864
Yeah.

00:36:10.864 --> 00:36:12.799
INT: What did you do
there during the day?

00:36:12.799 --> 00:36:14.000
CB: Nothing.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:15.869
Literally nothing.

00:36:15.869 --> 00:36:18.672
There was nothing to do, except
stand on-- you know, I mean,

00:36:18.672 --> 00:36:22.375
they kept us for hours
outside, counting us.

00:36:22.375 --> 00:36:24.811
But there was-- you
know, there was no work.

00:36:24.811 --> 00:36:25.679
We were waiting.

00:36:25.679 --> 00:36:28.682
We were in transition,
supposedly.

00:36:28.682 --> 00:36:31.017
At least we found out that
we were in transition.

00:36:31.017 --> 00:36:33.553
We couldn't figure
out how we got there.

00:36:33.553 --> 00:36:35.021
We were supposed
to have gotten--

00:36:35.021 --> 00:36:36.756
you know, we were
signed on a list,

00:36:36.756 --> 00:36:43.363
we were supposed to go
to Brünnlitz to work.

00:36:43.363 --> 00:36:44.364
So we were just waiting.

00:36:44.364 --> 00:36:45.865
We didn't know
what was happening.

00:36:45.865 --> 00:36:47.400
That was another
thing, you know, not

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:49.269
knowing, one way or the other.

00:36:52.005 --> 00:36:54.474
INT: Are there any
specific incidences

00:36:54.474 --> 00:36:56.476
that you remember from
Auschwitz that you'd

00:36:56.476 --> 00:36:57.610
like to share with us?

00:36:57.610 --> 00:36:59.646
CB: Well, one
specific incident is

00:36:59.646 --> 00:37:05.518
that I owe my life to Dr.
Mengele's change of heart,

00:37:05.518 --> 00:37:06.286
you know.

00:37:06.286 --> 00:37:09.289
There was one day that they
had took us through a selection

00:37:09.289 --> 00:37:11.458
again, and it was the only
time that my mother and I

00:37:11.458 --> 00:37:13.126
were separated.

00:37:13.126 --> 00:37:15.128
She had gone to--

00:37:15.128 --> 00:37:18.098
on the ruse of peeling
potatoes or something,

00:37:18.098 --> 00:37:21.167
which she thought she could
bring some potato skins back

00:37:21.167 --> 00:37:21.668
to--

00:37:21.668 --> 00:37:23.403
to eat.

00:37:23.403 --> 00:37:24.537
Turned out, it wasn't that.

00:37:24.537 --> 00:37:25.638
I think they were
supposed to give

00:37:25.638 --> 00:37:26.840
blood or something like that.

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:28.541
But anyway, they took
some of the women--

00:37:28.541 --> 00:37:31.444
35 or 40 women--

00:37:31.444 --> 00:37:32.745
to do work or something.

00:37:32.745 --> 00:37:37.784
But the rest of the barrack
was taken to-- for a selection.

00:37:37.784 --> 00:37:40.520
Again, we were told to
strip and walk through.

00:37:40.520 --> 00:37:44.924
And on the first run
through, Dr. Mengele

00:37:44.924 --> 00:37:49.028
pushed me to the left side
with some of the older women.

00:37:49.028 --> 00:37:50.597
And then, I don't
know what happened.

00:37:50.597 --> 00:37:52.465
He had a change of
heart, and told everybody

00:37:52.465 --> 00:37:55.068
to go through again.

00:37:55.068 --> 00:37:58.271
And when we went
through again, I just--

00:37:58.271 --> 00:38:00.907
I don't know how I got the
nerve, but I looked up at him

00:38:00.907 --> 00:38:02.675
and I said three
words in German--

00:38:02.675 --> 00:38:05.578
[SPEAKING GERMAN]
and he let me go.

00:38:05.578 --> 00:38:06.980
He let me go to the right.

00:38:06.980 --> 00:38:12.552
And I ran like crazy, clutching
my clothes in my hands,

00:38:12.552 --> 00:38:14.554
in the nude, out.

00:38:14.554 --> 00:38:16.356
INT: How old were
you at that time?

00:38:16.356 --> 00:38:18.825
CB: Well, I must have been 12.

00:38:18.825 --> 00:38:21.628
12 and a half, almost 13.

00:38:21.628 --> 00:38:27.166
Real age-- according to the
upped age, I was probably,

00:38:27.166 --> 00:38:28.301
what, two years older?

00:38:28.301 --> 00:38:31.204
So I would have been almost 14.

00:38:31.204 --> 00:38:34.007
INT: What do you remember
about Dr. Mengele that

00:38:34.007 --> 00:38:36.175
stands out in your mind?

00:38:36.175 --> 00:38:37.877
CB: He was a devil.

00:38:37.877 --> 00:38:39.812
That's what I-- a handsome--

00:38:39.812 --> 00:38:42.115
he was not a bad-looking
guy, you know?

00:38:42.115 --> 00:38:45.151
But what I remember-- he
had a pencil in his hand,

00:38:45.151 --> 00:38:49.322
and that's all he did was
point with his pencil.

00:38:49.322 --> 00:38:51.524
That was Dr. Mengele.

00:38:51.524 --> 00:38:54.727
That was my one brief
encounter, but I came out

00:38:54.727 --> 00:38:56.763
of it OK, you know?

00:38:56.763 --> 00:38:59.532
So I was lucky.

00:39:02.168 --> 00:39:04.303
INT: So when your
mother returned--

00:39:04.303 --> 00:39:05.972
CB: My mother
returned and found out

00:39:05.972 --> 00:39:08.374
that the barrack had
been taken for selection,

00:39:08.374 --> 00:39:10.076
and she was frantic--

00:39:10.076 --> 00:39:11.077
absolutely frantic.

00:39:11.077 --> 00:39:15.848
I remember having run
out from the selection,

00:39:15.848 --> 00:39:18.418
and my mother returning
and running up and down

00:39:18.418 --> 00:39:19.285
looking for me.

00:39:19.285 --> 00:39:23.823
I mean, she was absolutely
frantic, you know?

00:39:23.823 --> 00:39:25.892
I can imagine, you know,
what it would be like.

00:39:28.828 --> 00:39:31.798
INT: So how long were you
at Auschwitz, altogether?

00:39:31.798 --> 00:39:34.333
CB: Oh, I'm trying to remember
when he got us, finally.

00:39:34.333 --> 00:39:35.935
Schindler actually
came-- and now, see,

00:39:35.935 --> 00:39:36.869
that's another thing--

00:39:36.869 --> 00:39:39.572
I really didn't know
that, that he actually

00:39:39.572 --> 00:39:43.376
came for us, till
I found out later

00:39:43.376 --> 00:39:46.612
that he-- it was only
through his interference

00:39:46.612 --> 00:39:49.682
that we finally
got out, you know.

00:39:49.682 --> 00:39:52.952
Because all of us-- we
were lined up to go.

00:39:52.952 --> 00:39:55.021
They lined us up
again, and told us

00:39:55.021 --> 00:39:59.492
they were going to tattoo
us-- tattoo our number on us.

00:39:59.492 --> 00:40:01.727
And I was even asking my
mother, is it going to hurt?

00:40:01.727 --> 00:40:03.162
Is it going to hurt?

00:40:03.162 --> 00:40:07.700
And then, all of a sudden,
they shoved us into the cars,

00:40:07.700 --> 00:40:10.403
and we went off
without the tattoos.

00:40:10.403 --> 00:40:12.972
We couldn't-- you know,
everything was just--

00:40:12.972 --> 00:40:17.977
everything happened, and
you didn't understand why.

00:40:17.977 --> 00:40:22.682
We were there, definitely,
through a lot of snow and cold.

00:40:22.682 --> 00:40:26.585
So I would have to say we were
there through November and part

00:40:26.585 --> 00:40:27.186
of December.

00:40:27.186 --> 00:40:28.621
I would think so, you know.

00:40:28.621 --> 00:40:32.258
And then it took us about
three and a half days

00:40:32.258 --> 00:40:37.363
to make the trip
from Auschwitz to--

00:40:37.363 --> 00:40:38.497
my mother got very sick.

00:40:38.497 --> 00:40:39.265
She had pneumonia.

00:40:41.801 --> 00:40:44.303
She really got very, very sick.

00:40:44.303 --> 00:40:45.805
When we got to--

00:40:45.805 --> 00:40:49.975
to Brünnlitz, you
know, they came to--

00:40:49.975 --> 00:40:54.714
Schindler came to the-- to
the station to pick us up--

00:40:54.714 --> 00:40:56.916
you know, to the
railroad station--

00:40:56.916 --> 00:40:59.418
we couldn't believe that
we actually made it.

00:40:59.418 --> 00:41:00.553
INT: What do you remember--

00:41:00.553 --> 00:41:03.489
CB: Well, we saw the men
behind the wire, you know?

00:41:03.489 --> 00:41:05.858
And we couldn't believe-- and
they couldn't recognize us,

00:41:05.858 --> 00:41:07.760
because we were all shaved.

00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:10.729
They left us with hair,
and got all their women

00:41:10.729 --> 00:41:12.998
without any hair, you know?

00:41:12.998 --> 00:41:15.167
So, the barracks--

00:41:15.167 --> 00:41:20.506
I remember that we slept
on top of the factory,

00:41:20.506 --> 00:41:22.308
and it was warm.

00:41:22.308 --> 00:41:23.175
I remember that.

00:41:23.175 --> 00:41:24.944
We felt good and warm.

00:41:24.944 --> 00:41:29.915
But he hadn't had the time,
yet, to build any bunks,

00:41:29.915 --> 00:41:32.418
so we all slept on the floor.

00:41:32.418 --> 00:41:34.887
It was only later that he--

00:41:34.887 --> 00:41:37.556
that they built bunks for us.

00:41:37.556 --> 00:41:41.393
And in this particular place,
we shared two to a bunk--

00:41:41.393 --> 00:41:43.395
so that was kind of
nice to not to have

00:41:43.395 --> 00:41:47.032
to share with five people.

00:41:47.032 --> 00:41:50.402
They were triple bunks,
you know-- three tiers.

00:41:50.402 --> 00:41:56.008
But the distinct memory
is that it was warm.

00:41:56.008 --> 00:41:59.578
Again, he got us some
soup and some coffee,

00:41:59.578 --> 00:42:03.716
and we each got a round
little bowl and a pot-- which

00:42:03.716 --> 00:42:05.484
my mother still
has to this day--

00:42:05.484 --> 00:42:10.656
red enamelled pot,
enamelled pan.

00:42:10.656 --> 00:42:12.858
The pan was for soup,
the pot was for coffee--

00:42:12.858 --> 00:42:14.193
which, you could call it coffee.

00:42:14.193 --> 00:42:16.261
I mean, it was just
water, really--

00:42:16.261 --> 00:42:18.497
and a piece of bread.

00:42:18.497 --> 00:42:19.965
But one of the
problems-- you know,

00:42:19.965 --> 00:42:23.035
we felt safe with Schindler,
but one of the problems

00:42:23.035 --> 00:42:24.503
was that there was
really no food.

00:42:24.503 --> 00:42:27.172
At that point, this was
towards the end of the war,

00:42:27.172 --> 00:42:31.310
and supplies were
very hard to come by.

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:33.746
People-- there were quite a
few sick people at that point.

00:42:33.746 --> 00:42:35.714
The trip was very hard.

00:42:35.714 --> 00:42:40.552
In the cold cattle cars,
a lot of people got sick.

00:42:40.552 --> 00:42:41.787
It was a problem, you know?

00:42:41.787 --> 00:42:43.789
INT: What happened with
your mother's pneumonia?

00:42:43.789 --> 00:42:46.525
My mother, she was
absolutely remarkable.

00:42:46.525 --> 00:42:50.329
She was very, very sick, and
there were no medications,

00:42:50.329 --> 00:42:51.830
you know.

00:42:51.830 --> 00:42:54.333
She got finished
with the pneumonia,

00:42:54.333 --> 00:42:56.468
but she had kidney
problems after that.

00:42:56.468 --> 00:42:59.004
She was very swollen
towards the end of the--

00:42:59.004 --> 00:43:01.440
ot the camp, you know.

00:43:01.440 --> 00:43:03.776
We all were kind of sick.

00:43:03.776 --> 00:43:05.878
In Plaszow, I had
had my experiences.

00:43:05.878 --> 00:43:09.214
I had-- I forgot to say that--

00:43:09.214 --> 00:43:13.285
I had contracted scarlet
fever, and ended up

00:43:13.285 --> 00:43:16.722
at the epidemical
hospital, where--

00:43:16.722 --> 00:43:18.690
which was kind of
dangerous at the time,

00:43:18.690 --> 00:43:21.093
you know, to be sick at all.

00:43:21.093 --> 00:43:23.295
But at the hospital,
unfortunately,

00:43:23.295 --> 00:43:25.964
as I got over the
scarlet fever, I

00:43:25.964 --> 00:43:28.867
caught typhoid
fever, because there

00:43:28.867 --> 00:43:31.203
were no sanitary conditions.

00:43:31.203 --> 00:43:33.105
And I got over
the typhoid fever,

00:43:33.105 --> 00:43:34.706
but that left me with jaundice.

00:43:34.706 --> 00:43:36.408
I was kind of yellow
for a long time.

00:43:36.408 --> 00:43:38.844
And that left me with
a liver impairment,

00:43:38.844 --> 00:43:42.748
which then flared
up in Brünnlitz.

00:43:42.748 --> 00:43:45.617
And I ended up in the infirmary
with kind of an enlarged liver.

00:43:45.617 --> 00:43:49.121
And it was only through the
good graces of Mrs. Schindler--

00:43:49.121 --> 00:43:54.059
Emily-- who every day came with
a pot of farina that she had

00:43:54.059 --> 00:43:57.996
cooked herself, you
know, and fed us--

00:43:57.996 --> 00:44:01.500
fed us sick people, that
we survived, really.

00:44:01.500 --> 00:44:06.405
Because that was the only
nourishment that we got.

00:44:06.405 --> 00:44:10.275
So that was the story.

00:44:10.275 --> 00:44:11.343
I worked there, too.

00:44:11.343 --> 00:44:14.046
I mean, we all worked on
the-- on the machinery.

00:44:14.046 --> 00:44:16.048
INT: What did you
do on the machinery?

00:44:16.048 --> 00:44:19.785
CB: Well, to start with,
another girl and I--

00:44:19.785 --> 00:44:22.154
we were the youngest there.

00:44:22.154 --> 00:44:24.423
According to Schindler,
we had the small hands

00:44:24.423 --> 00:44:27.459
that were able to fit
into the large machinery

00:44:27.459 --> 00:44:30.595
and clean the large
machinery from inside out.

00:44:30.595 --> 00:44:32.230
And that's what
we started doing.

00:44:32.230 --> 00:44:35.400
We cleaned the large
machinery, you know.

00:44:35.400 --> 00:44:38.036
And then I worked on
a lathe, and then I

00:44:38.036 --> 00:44:43.308
worked on a calibrating
machine for a while.

00:44:43.308 --> 00:44:44.710
An interesting
thing is, there was

00:44:44.710 --> 00:44:46.878
a row of us on the
calibrating machine,

00:44:46.878 --> 00:44:50.482
you know, sitting there
and measuring the items

00:44:50.482 --> 00:44:53.218
as they came off the
assembly line, to make sure

00:44:53.218 --> 00:44:54.786
that they were correct.

00:44:54.786 --> 00:44:56.955
And they weren't, of course,
but that was the idea.

00:44:56.955 --> 00:45:00.192
I mean, Schindler didn't
want us to produce anything

00:45:00.192 --> 00:45:02.727
that was-- that would work.

00:45:02.727 --> 00:45:03.795
INT: Did he tell you that?

00:45:03.795 --> 00:45:06.097
CB: Yes, he did tell us that.

00:45:06.097 --> 00:45:09.134
I mean, he told the
supervisors that, you know.

00:45:09.134 --> 00:45:12.170
And the calibrating machines
were fixed in such a way

00:45:12.170 --> 00:45:14.873
that if somebody checked
it, it would show right.

00:45:14.873 --> 00:45:16.842
But it wasn't right.

00:45:16.842 --> 00:45:19.144
But the interesting thing
is, as we sat on the line,

00:45:19.144 --> 00:45:22.047
the-- you know, with
the calibrating--

00:45:22.047 --> 00:45:25.517
everybody talked about food.

00:45:25.517 --> 00:45:27.519
And they talked about
the elegant dinners

00:45:27.519 --> 00:45:30.956
and elegant desserts that
they would prepare and cook.

00:45:30.956 --> 00:45:32.357
I mean, it was
incredible, the way

00:45:32.357 --> 00:45:35.460
they talked about,
you know, fancy meals.

00:45:35.460 --> 00:45:36.561
As if that gave--

00:45:36.561 --> 00:45:39.364
you konw, that's all they
talked about was food.

00:45:39.364 --> 00:45:40.432
Because we were so hungry.

00:45:40.432 --> 00:45:43.134
I think that was
the reason for it.

00:45:43.134 --> 00:45:45.270
INT: While you were
working at Brünnlitz,

00:45:45.270 --> 00:45:47.305
did you see a lot
of Schindler there?

00:45:47.305 --> 00:45:51.376
CB: Yes, he used to come on
the factory floor quite often.

00:45:51.376 --> 00:45:55.680
As a matter of fact, one day
he was visited by Mr. Titsch

00:45:55.680 --> 00:46:00.819
from Madritsch factory,
who came to visit.

00:46:00.819 --> 00:46:03.588
And they came by, as I was
cleaning one of the machines,

00:46:03.588 --> 00:46:07.025
and they stopped by, and
Mr. Titsch spoke to me

00:46:07.025 --> 00:46:10.662
and asked me, you
know, how things were,

00:46:10.662 --> 00:46:13.999
and if there was anything
that I would want.

00:46:13.999 --> 00:46:16.501
And at the time, I was
wearing still the clogs--

00:46:16.501 --> 00:46:19.304
the wooden clogs--
and it was winter.

00:46:19.304 --> 00:46:23.975
And I said to Mr. Titsch, ah,
if only we could have shoes.

00:46:23.975 --> 00:46:28.847
About a week and a
half later, a load of--

00:46:28.847 --> 00:46:31.116
well, now, they weren't shoes,
but they had-- you know,

00:46:31.116 --> 00:46:34.119
they were wooden soles, but
at least they had some sort

00:46:34.119 --> 00:46:37.021
of a canvas tops--

00:46:37.021 --> 00:46:38.590
was delivered for the women.

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:40.392
Now, I don't know
whether Mr. Titsch did it

00:46:40.392 --> 00:46:42.827
or whether Schindler did it,
but Schindler was with him,

00:46:42.827 --> 00:46:43.328
you know.

00:46:43.328 --> 00:46:47.398
It was nice to have
gotten some shoes.

00:46:47.398 --> 00:46:51.736
And then another time,
Goeth came to visit.

00:46:51.736 --> 00:46:53.271
INT: What do you
remember about that?

00:46:53.271 --> 00:46:58.143
CB: I remember we were
lined up to greet him,

00:46:58.143 --> 00:47:00.245
and Schindler walked
through with Goeth.

00:47:00.245 --> 00:47:04.782
And of course, in Plaszow, you
didn't dare lift your eyelids

00:47:04.782 --> 00:47:05.617
to look at Goeth.

00:47:05.617 --> 00:47:08.286
I mean, your head
was always down.

00:47:08.286 --> 00:47:11.456
Well, we felt so
protected by Schindler

00:47:11.456 --> 00:47:13.424
that we looked at him.

00:47:13.424 --> 00:47:17.362
For the first time, really
looked in the guy's face.

00:47:17.362 --> 00:47:19.664
And it was just-- it was
a good feeling, you know,

00:47:19.664 --> 00:47:22.534
to be able to look the
monster in his face.

00:47:25.737 --> 00:47:27.405
It was even better
later on in Poland,

00:47:27.405 --> 00:47:29.340
when we returned to
Poland after the war,

00:47:29.340 --> 00:47:33.444
to find out that he had
been caught, judged guilty,

00:47:33.444 --> 00:47:36.247
and was facing hanging.

00:47:36.247 --> 00:47:38.149
Just what he meted
out to other people.

00:47:41.819 --> 00:47:46.224
INT: So what do you remember
about the end of your stay

00:47:46.224 --> 00:47:46.925
at Brünnlitz?

00:47:46.925 --> 00:47:48.293
How did things change?

00:47:48.293 --> 00:47:51.763
Were your SS guards
still around?

00:47:51.763 --> 00:47:52.830
What happened?

00:47:52.830 --> 00:47:56.634
CB: Well, the SS-- it was
interesting, because the war--

00:47:56.634 --> 00:48:03.074
we heard-- we had underground
radio that we listened to,

00:48:03.074 --> 00:48:08.546
so we knew that the war
was over on the 7th of May.

00:48:08.546 --> 00:48:12.216
But-- and of course,
Schindler left under the--

00:48:12.216 --> 00:48:17.088
with some of the people
who escorted him out of--

00:48:17.088 --> 00:48:19.323
into the American zone.

00:48:19.323 --> 00:48:22.827
However, we were waiting for
the Russians to liberate us.

00:48:22.827 --> 00:48:25.930
We were surrounded
by the black shirts.

00:48:25.930 --> 00:48:33.337
There were huge groups of them
still in the surrounding woods

00:48:33.337 --> 00:48:34.906
of Czechoslovakia--

00:48:34.906 --> 00:48:40.211
or at that area, anyway.

00:48:40.211 --> 00:48:42.847
The SS-- from what
we understand--

00:48:42.847 --> 00:48:44.949
from what I remember,
what I understood--

00:48:44.949 --> 00:48:47.051
that the two grave--

00:48:47.051 --> 00:48:49.654
even though we were under
the protection of Schindler,

00:48:49.654 --> 00:48:53.925
there was a commandant that
was in charge of the camp,

00:48:53.925 --> 00:48:55.126
of the labor camp.

00:48:55.126 --> 00:48:59.497
I mean, Schindler only used
the labor force in his factory.

00:48:59.497 --> 00:49:03.835
The commandant was supposedly
in charge of the prisoners.

00:49:03.835 --> 00:49:07.905
Supposedly, there were two
huge graves dug already for us.

00:49:07.905 --> 00:49:09.974
Now, I don't know whether
that is true or not,

00:49:09.974 --> 00:49:11.642
that's what I heard.

00:49:11.642 --> 00:49:14.045
Schindler-- we also
heard that Schindler

00:49:14.045 --> 00:49:16.781
got the guards
drunk in some way,

00:49:16.781 --> 00:49:21.252
and sent them off
on a train, away.

00:49:21.252 --> 00:49:27.425
One guard-- and he gave
the Jewish policemen

00:49:27.425 --> 00:49:31.562
guns to protect us
while he went away.

00:49:31.562 --> 00:49:35.366
And so, for two days,
we had protection

00:49:35.366 --> 00:49:39.837
from Jewish prisoners
holding rifles

00:49:39.837 --> 00:49:45.476
against any marauders that
might be on the outside.

00:49:45.476 --> 00:49:52.516
We understood there
was one terrible guy,

00:49:52.516 --> 00:49:55.920
and somehow they caught him
in some way and kept him.

00:49:55.920 --> 00:49:58.723
Because I know that, when
the Russians liberated us,

00:49:58.723 --> 00:50:02.326
they hanged him, and they wanted
us all to watch the hanging.

00:50:02.326 --> 00:50:04.161
INT: Was this a
German that was hung?

00:50:04.161 --> 00:50:05.162
CB: Yeah.

00:50:05.162 --> 00:50:06.297
INT: Who did the hanging?

00:50:06.297 --> 00:50:08.199
CB: The Russians.

00:50:08.199 --> 00:50:10.401
The Russian army was a
very interesting army

00:50:10.401 --> 00:50:14.405
when they came in, unlike an
army that you think marches

00:50:14.405 --> 00:50:18.576
to a-- to a goose-stepping
beat, you know.

00:50:18.576 --> 00:50:22.213
They were very incredible.

00:50:22.213 --> 00:50:25.916
There were women, and
young boys, and older men.

00:50:25.916 --> 00:50:29.053
It was just--
[PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS]

00:50:29.053 --> 00:50:30.955
they weren't in
ranks of any sort,

00:50:30.955 --> 00:50:33.257
they just came, you
know, with one of them

00:50:33.257 --> 00:50:37.595
on a horse to start with,
to tell us that we were free

00:50:37.595 --> 00:50:39.663
and to tell us to
leave the camp.

00:50:39.663 --> 00:50:40.831
Well, we were afraid.

00:50:40.831 --> 00:50:43.367
We did not know how to
walk outside of the camp

00:50:43.367 --> 00:50:47.438
without walking in
fives, you know.

00:50:47.438 --> 00:50:52.610
But after a while, you
know, in a few days,

00:50:52.610 --> 00:50:55.779
we started back
to Poland walking.

00:50:55.779 --> 00:50:58.315
And, you know, all the
bridges were blown up,

00:50:58.315 --> 00:51:00.484
and all the roads were--

00:51:00.484 --> 00:51:04.722
it took us-- let's see now,
we were liberated on the 9th,

00:51:04.722 --> 00:51:07.925
and it took us, I would
say, a good two weeks

00:51:07.925 --> 00:51:10.027
to get back to Krakow.

00:51:10.027 --> 00:51:12.763
INT: This was the
9th of May, 1945?

00:51:12.763 --> 00:51:14.164
CB: '45, Mm-hm.

00:51:14.164 --> 00:51:17.301
INT: Before you get back to
Krakow, let me just ask you--

00:51:17.301 --> 00:51:19.403
did you see Schindler
leave the camp?

00:51:19.403 --> 00:51:21.138
CB: No I did not, no.

00:51:21.138 --> 00:51:24.108
I understand he left at night.

00:51:24.108 --> 00:51:26.777
There were some people
who did accompany him,

00:51:26.777 --> 00:51:28.879
and some people who
did see him leave,

00:51:28.879 --> 00:51:31.248
but I was not one of them.

00:51:31.248 --> 00:51:32.816
No.

00:51:32.816 --> 00:51:37.254
INT: So after leaving the camp,
how did you get back to Krakow?

00:51:37.254 --> 00:51:39.156
CB: We walked, primarily.

00:51:39.156 --> 00:51:42.660
We walked, or we hitched some
rides or with-- on carts,

00:51:42.660 --> 00:51:44.028
if people would take us.

00:51:44.028 --> 00:51:48.332
The Czechs were incredibly
kind people, the kindest people

00:51:48.332 --> 00:51:50.000
I've met, really.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:51.702
They were wonderful.

00:51:51.702 --> 00:51:53.504
They really extended themselves.

00:51:53.504 --> 00:51:57.274
They shared whatever
they had with us.

00:51:57.274 --> 00:51:58.942
Really good people.

00:51:58.942 --> 00:52:02.446
So, you know, by
walking and by hiking

00:52:02.446 --> 00:52:05.115
and by hitchhiking, and
doing all of those things,

00:52:05.115 --> 00:52:07.951
we finally got back to Krakow.

00:52:07.951 --> 00:52:09.787
INT: Who were you
with at the time?

00:52:09.787 --> 00:52:12.389
CB: My mother and my
father, the three of us,

00:52:12.389 --> 00:52:15.192
because we met in the last camp.

00:52:15.192 --> 00:52:17.461
INT: And how old were
you at this time?

00:52:17.461 --> 00:52:21.198
CB: I was 13, almost
14, because my birthday

00:52:21.198 --> 00:52:24.935
was on the 28th of May.

00:52:24.935 --> 00:52:27.905
INT: So what do you remember
about going back to Krakow?

00:52:27.905 --> 00:52:30.374
CB: I remember--

00:52:30.374 --> 00:52:34.077
I remember that we
weren't welcomed.

00:52:34.077 --> 00:52:36.513
Here we thought we
had survived the war,

00:52:36.513 --> 00:52:39.983
and we would be,
you know, welcomed,

00:52:39.983 --> 00:52:42.920
but we weren't at all.

00:52:42.920 --> 00:52:44.688
If there was any--

00:52:44.688 --> 00:52:48.992
you know, that's when I
really felt anti-Semitism.

00:52:48.992 --> 00:52:52.396
We were really told, you know,
we shouldn't have survived,

00:52:52.396 --> 00:52:56.333
Hitler didn't do enough.

00:52:56.333 --> 00:52:59.336
You felt like you didn't
want to stay there

00:52:59.336 --> 00:53:01.905
for a very long time.

00:53:01.905 --> 00:53:04.241
On the 28th of May,
it was my birthday,

00:53:04.241 --> 00:53:08.345
and the only thing I wanted
was to go to a movie.

00:53:08.345 --> 00:53:11.615
So my mother arranged for
me to go to the movie--

00:53:11.615 --> 00:53:13.116
but I didn't have any clothes.

00:53:13.116 --> 00:53:16.153
We were staying
with some people,

00:53:16.153 --> 00:53:19.856
and I borrowed a skirt
and a top from this lady.

00:53:19.856 --> 00:53:23.727
But the skirt-- I had to wind
like three times around me.

00:53:23.727 --> 00:53:30.567
I had weighed 65 pounds, and
I was as tall as I am now.

00:53:30.567 --> 00:53:31.802
So I was pretty skinny.

00:53:34.371 --> 00:53:38.842
Yeah, 35 kilos--
70 pounds, yeah.

00:53:38.842 --> 00:53:40.777
But I had-- you know,
I went to the movies.

00:53:40.777 --> 00:53:44.581
I remember to this day what
I saw, it was Deanna Durbin.

00:53:44.581 --> 00:53:48.018
And it was some sort of
a show called, in Polish,

00:53:48.018 --> 00:53:48.785
[SPEAKING POLISH].

00:53:48.785 --> 00:53:53.223
I mean, it was some sort of a
school for girls-- you know,

00:53:53.223 --> 00:53:54.624
adolescent girls.

00:53:54.624 --> 00:53:56.960
And I was-- to me it
was absolutely charming,

00:53:56.960 --> 00:54:00.530
and she had a beautiful voice,
and she was singing in it.

00:54:00.530 --> 00:54:03.667
But shock of shocks, I saw
myself for the first time

00:54:03.667 --> 00:54:05.736
in a full-length mirror.

00:54:05.736 --> 00:54:08.472
I couldn't believe
what I saw, you know.

00:54:08.472 --> 00:54:11.308
I mean, my hair had just
started growing out,

00:54:11.308 --> 00:54:15.345
and I was skinny as
anything, and I looked awful.

00:54:15.345 --> 00:54:17.681
You know, like a
skeleton, practically.

00:54:17.681 --> 00:54:21.885
So that's how I
remember my birthday.

00:54:21.885 --> 00:54:25.589
Anyway, I also realized
that I didn't know anything.

00:54:25.589 --> 00:54:30.193
I had-- I didn't
know how to write.

00:54:30.193 --> 00:54:32.796
I knew how to read, because
one of the things I forgot

00:54:32.796 --> 00:54:35.866
to tell you was that in
Plaszow, they brought books

00:54:35.866 --> 00:54:38.568
from all over to burn them.

00:54:38.568 --> 00:54:41.705
And the women who were in
charge of burning the books

00:54:41.705 --> 00:54:43.273
used to steal them--

00:54:43.273 --> 00:54:45.242
under penalty of death--

00:54:45.242 --> 00:54:47.410
hide them on them, bring
them back to the barracks,

00:54:47.410 --> 00:54:50.714
and pass them around to
read at night, you know.

00:54:50.714 --> 00:54:51.648
And we would just--

00:54:51.648 --> 00:54:56.353
so we read, you know,
by the night light.

00:54:56.353 --> 00:54:58.588
I knew how to read, but I
didn't know how to write.

00:54:58.588 --> 00:54:59.489
And I had lost--

00:54:59.489 --> 00:55:03.360
you know, I was 14, and I
only had two years of school.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:07.397
So the important thing
was to get caught up.

00:55:07.397 --> 00:55:11.534
So I started learning
as quickly as possible.

00:55:11.534 --> 00:55:16.373
My parents got me a tutor,
and I tried to cram in as much

00:55:16.373 --> 00:55:17.173
as possible.

00:55:17.173 --> 00:55:18.508
INT: Was this in Krakow?

00:55:18.508 --> 00:55:20.677
CB: That was in Krakow.

00:55:20.677 --> 00:55:23.713
We got there, as I said, in May.

00:55:23.713 --> 00:55:25.615
And I had the
summer to do it in,

00:55:25.615 --> 00:55:30.353
because I was trying to make
it into school in September.

00:55:30.353 --> 00:55:35.692
And I took the exams, and I
made it into the gymnasium.

00:55:35.692 --> 00:55:40.797
I made up six years of
school in one summer,

00:55:40.797 --> 00:55:43.433
and made it into-- there
was only two Jewish girls

00:55:43.433 --> 00:55:44.334
were accepted.

00:55:44.334 --> 00:55:46.136
I was one of them.

00:55:46.136 --> 00:55:52.042
However, in September, there
was another pogrom in Poland.

00:55:52.042 --> 00:55:54.577
And it was at that point
that my parents decided--

00:55:54.577 --> 00:55:56.713
we-- well, they
went back, really,

00:55:56.713 --> 00:55:59.149
to see if there was anybody
left from the family.

00:55:59.149 --> 00:56:01.317
And since there was nobody
left from the family

00:56:01.317 --> 00:56:11.461
that we knew of, they let my
uncle know, in Israel, and also

00:56:11.461 --> 00:56:15.598
my uncle in the United
States, that we survived.

00:56:15.598 --> 00:56:20.303
And my parents decided Poland
was not the place to stay.

00:56:20.303 --> 00:56:27.644
And I was in school for about
four weeks, just September.

00:56:27.644 --> 00:56:32.348
And in October, we smuggled
over the border, out of Poland.

00:56:32.348 --> 00:56:36.653
And already at that point,
Poland was closing its borders.

00:56:36.653 --> 00:56:42.792
And we smuggled in a Russian
truck into Bratislava.

00:56:42.792 --> 00:56:47.597
And from Bratislava, we
made our way into Prague--

00:56:47.597 --> 00:56:49.632
back to Czechoslovakia.

00:56:49.632 --> 00:56:51.668
And from Prague, we went--

00:56:51.668 --> 00:56:55.505
we waited there for
about a week and a half,

00:56:55.505 --> 00:56:59.242
and then we were taken
over the border--

00:56:59.242 --> 00:57:01.511
the German-Czech border.

00:57:01.511 --> 00:57:05.515
In the middle of the
night, we walked across.

00:57:05.515 --> 00:57:08.017
We missed the-- we made
it through the Czech,

00:57:08.017 --> 00:57:11.888
but didn't quite make it behind
the border of the Americans,

00:57:11.888 --> 00:57:13.456
but they let us in.

00:57:13.456 --> 00:57:16.359
And we made it into
Hof, and from Hof

00:57:16.359 --> 00:57:19.896
into Landsberg, the
displaced persons camp,

00:57:19.896 --> 00:57:22.632
where we stayed
for a little while.

00:57:22.632 --> 00:57:25.134
And then into
Mindelheim, where we

00:57:25.134 --> 00:57:28.705
stayed for a year and a half,
and then the United States.

00:57:28.705 --> 00:57:30.039
INT: Let me stop you right here.

00:57:30.039 --> 00:57:31.207
We're going to change
the tape and we'll

00:57:31.207 --> 00:57:32.709
talk a little bit
more about this.

00:57:32.709 --> 00:57:33.843
CB: OK.

00:57:34.844 --> 00:57:39.048
INT: --25, 1996 in
Camarillo, California.

00:57:39.048 --> 00:57:41.150
Mrs. Biniaz, when
we left off, you

00:57:41.150 --> 00:57:44.787
were telling us how you
traveled through Germany

00:57:44.787 --> 00:57:46.255
to come to the United States.

00:57:46.255 --> 00:57:48.291
But let's back up a little bit.

00:57:48.291 --> 00:57:51.527
And why don't you tell us what
it was like at the DP camp

00:57:51.527 --> 00:57:53.696
when you got there.

00:57:53.696 --> 00:57:56.866
CB: Well, there
were people from all

00:57:56.866 --> 00:58:02.271
over who had no way of going
back to their countries.

00:58:02.271 --> 00:58:06.042
And again, we lived in
barracks and buildings.

00:58:08.678 --> 00:58:13.883
Lots of people got married,
you know, and some of them

00:58:13.883 --> 00:58:18.287
actually started
on having babies.

00:58:18.287 --> 00:58:22.892
But we had lived in camp so many
years that my parents decided

00:58:22.892 --> 00:58:25.995
this was not the
way to live anymore

00:58:25.995 --> 00:58:29.632
and started to look
on the outside.

00:58:29.632 --> 00:58:33.536
Went to a place called
Mindelheim a small community

00:58:33.536 --> 00:58:35.938
in Schwabenland.

00:58:35.938 --> 00:58:38.074
It's on the way
to Memmingen. It's

00:58:38.074 --> 00:58:44.313
between Munich and Memmingen,
or Augsburg and Memmingen,

00:58:44.313 --> 00:58:46.916
the home of the river Mindel.

00:58:46.916 --> 00:58:50.253
It's very charming, very small.

00:58:50.253 --> 00:58:54.590
They were able to find
[PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS]

00:58:54.590 --> 00:58:55.491
an apartment--

00:58:55.491 --> 00:58:59.295
a requisition-- a room,
really, from a woman

00:58:59.295 --> 00:59:04.033
whose husband was perished
in the war, but was a Nazi.

00:59:04.033 --> 00:59:06.936
It was-- wasn't really
fair, in retrospect,

00:59:06.936 --> 00:59:07.937
to do this to somebody.

00:59:07.937 --> 00:59:11.173
I mean, she had
nothing to do with it.

00:59:11.173 --> 00:59:14.143
But that's the way
it was after the war.

00:59:14.143 --> 00:59:16.946
But we lived in her apartment.

00:59:16.946 --> 00:59:19.815
She was actually the
caretaker of the bank,

00:59:19.815 --> 00:59:20.783
and we lived upstairs.

00:59:20.783 --> 00:59:21.884
It was an attic apartment.

00:59:21.884 --> 00:59:23.552
It wasn't very much, really.

00:59:23.552 --> 00:59:27.023
But it was a better place
than living in a camp.

00:59:27.023 --> 00:59:30.192
And we went on
German ration cards,

00:59:30.192 --> 00:59:34.663
so we didn't even get
anything from the camp.

00:59:34.663 --> 00:59:38.501
We did get packages
from UNRRA once

00:59:38.501 --> 00:59:41.704
in a while, which was wonderful
to get that piece of chocolate,

00:59:41.704 --> 00:59:44.306
and piece of soap.

00:59:44.306 --> 00:59:47.243
And in the meantime,
we had contacted

00:59:47.243 --> 00:59:51.514
my uncle in the United States,
and my uncle in Israel.

00:59:51.514 --> 00:59:54.884
And they were both
working feverishly

00:59:54.884 --> 00:59:59.455
to send us affidavits
to come out.

00:59:59.455 --> 01:00:03.459
But it took a year
and a half for us.

01:00:03.459 --> 01:00:05.461
But that was my--

01:00:05.461 --> 01:00:08.297
that was my return
to normalcy, really.

01:00:08.297 --> 01:00:11.233
And I'm very grateful for having
lived for a year and a half

01:00:11.233 --> 01:00:16.372
in that German town,
because it just

01:00:16.372 --> 01:00:22.244
made me work my way through
hate, anger, and all of that.

01:00:22.244 --> 01:00:26.649
And I left feeling
pretty good, you know?

01:00:26.649 --> 01:00:28.150
INT: When you first
arrived there,

01:00:28.150 --> 01:00:30.185
did you feel a lot
of hate and anger?

01:00:30.185 --> 01:00:31.854
CB: Oh yes, of course.

01:00:31.854 --> 01:00:34.590
I mean, I had been
deprived of my childhood,

01:00:34.590 --> 01:00:39.028
you know, and really,
my teenage years.

01:00:39.028 --> 01:00:42.698
By the time I came to the
United States, I was 16.

01:00:42.698 --> 01:00:47.736
So in essence, from
eight to 16 was gone.

01:00:47.736 --> 01:00:52.308
But I had a very good
experience in Mindelheim.

01:00:52.308 --> 01:00:54.743
Just by chance, I worked--

01:00:54.743 --> 01:00:58.414
I went to a convent.

01:00:58.414 --> 01:01:00.482
And there was an
elderly nun there.

01:01:00.482 --> 01:01:07.423
She was 92 years old,
and I was 14 and a half.

01:01:07.423 --> 01:01:10.459
And she was going to teach
me English and German,

01:01:10.459 --> 01:01:13.362
because I didn't
know any at the time.

01:01:13.362 --> 01:01:14.997
She had been a cloistered nun.

01:01:14.997 --> 01:01:18.400
This was a semi-cloistered
establishment in the sense

01:01:18.400 --> 01:01:21.804
that the nuns didn't go
out, but the public came in.

01:01:21.804 --> 01:01:24.673
It was a school for girls.

01:01:24.673 --> 01:01:26.642
She had entered the convent--

01:01:26.642 --> 01:01:28.410
it was called the
English Institute.

01:01:28.410 --> 01:01:32.147
The mother house was in London.

01:01:32.147 --> 01:01:33.816
She had entered the
convent at the age

01:01:33.816 --> 01:01:40.622
of 16 because of a broken love
affair and had never left it.

01:01:40.622 --> 01:01:46.395
She did not know what it was
like on the outside, really.

01:01:46.395 --> 01:01:52.000
She accepted me totally for
what I was, which was wonderful,

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:53.302
you know?

01:01:53.302 --> 01:01:55.137
And she was very kind.

01:01:58.674 --> 01:02:01.944
It's the only time I cry,
when I think about her.

01:02:04.980 --> 01:02:08.517
She was good, good human being.

01:02:08.517 --> 01:02:15.791
[PAUSES FOR 6 SECONDS] I had
a good relationship with her

01:02:15.791 --> 01:02:16.725
for two years--

01:02:16.725 --> 01:02:18.360
I mean, year and a half.

01:02:18.360 --> 01:02:23.832
And then, we corresponded in the
United States when I came here.

01:02:23.832 --> 01:02:25.200
She died at the age of 94.

01:02:27.836 --> 01:02:28.737
I have her letters.

01:02:28.737 --> 01:02:36.178
[PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS]
Those were good Germans.

01:02:36.178 --> 01:02:37.512
Not everybody was bad.

01:02:37.512 --> 01:02:42.284
[PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] I
think living in Germany

01:02:42.284 --> 01:02:48.457
taught me one thing, that
evil can happen anywhere,

01:02:48.457 --> 01:02:52.294
with any human being,
if you give it a chance.

01:02:52.294 --> 01:03:00.936
[PAUSES FOR 8 SECONDS] OK.

01:03:04.873 --> 01:03:07.609
INT: What do you remember about
coming to the United States?

01:03:11.446 --> 01:03:17.052
CB: We arrived in New York
after 11 days on the boat.

01:03:17.052 --> 01:03:20.856
And we came on a troop ship.

01:03:20.856 --> 01:03:25.427
We were 60 women in
one of the cabins,

01:03:25.427 --> 01:03:30.766
you know, slept five to a bunk
because it was a troop ship.

01:03:30.766 --> 01:03:35.570
Everybody was seasick except me,
so I ate everybody's ice cream

01:03:35.570 --> 01:03:39.207
and enjoyed it tremendously.

01:03:39.207 --> 01:03:40.442
We arrived in New York.

01:03:40.442 --> 01:03:45.313
My uncle came from
Des Moines and met us

01:03:45.313 --> 01:03:47.983
with his brand new car.

01:03:47.983 --> 01:03:52.521
It was one of the new
Cadillacs that just came off

01:03:52.521 --> 01:03:56.892
the assembly line in 1947.

01:03:56.892 --> 01:03:59.895
We stayed in New
York for a few days.

01:03:59.895 --> 01:04:00.996
It was exhilarating.

01:04:00.996 --> 01:04:03.064
New York was very
exciting at the time,

01:04:03.064 --> 01:04:07.435
you know, Broadway, and lights,
and the neon lights everywhere.

01:04:07.435 --> 01:04:10.372
It was just beautiful.

01:04:10.372 --> 01:04:15.543
And he drove us, then,
from New York to Iowa,

01:04:15.543 --> 01:04:17.145
which was very nice.

01:04:17.145 --> 01:04:21.483
Get to see part of the
country, you know, that way.

01:04:21.483 --> 01:04:23.051
We didn't stay very
long in New York.

01:04:23.051 --> 01:04:25.553
We stayed about
three and a half--

01:04:25.553 --> 01:04:26.955
maybe three or four days.

01:04:26.955 --> 01:04:27.656
That's all.

01:04:27.656 --> 01:04:29.491
Yeah

01:04:29.491 --> 01:04:35.463
INT: So when you began your new
life in Iowa, what did you do?

01:04:35.463 --> 01:04:36.831
Did you become a student again?

01:04:36.831 --> 01:04:37.399
Did you work?

01:04:37.399 --> 01:04:38.133
CB: Right away.

01:04:38.133 --> 01:04:40.302
As a matter of fact,
I-- right away,

01:04:40.302 --> 01:04:42.103
as soon as we got
to Des Moines--

01:04:42.103 --> 01:04:44.072
it was in the summer--

01:04:44.072 --> 01:04:46.474
I signed up for summer school.

01:04:46.474 --> 01:04:47.909
I presented my book.

01:04:47.909 --> 01:04:50.578
I had been tutored in Germany.

01:04:50.578 --> 01:04:57.085
I you know-- my English nun
taught me English and German,

01:04:57.085 --> 01:05:01.990
but I also was tutored
in mathematics and Latin

01:05:01.990 --> 01:05:04.359
and took violin lessons.

01:05:04.359 --> 01:05:08.163
And fortunately, I brought
all my notebooks with me.

01:05:08.163 --> 01:05:11.199
And I submitted them
to the high school,

01:05:11.199 --> 01:05:13.735
and they looked them over.

01:05:13.735 --> 01:05:17.338
And they said that I had
covered enough material

01:05:17.338 --> 01:05:19.908
to enter the 12th grade.

01:05:19.908 --> 01:05:22.377
However, I did need
the requirement

01:05:22.377 --> 01:05:29.484
of American history, which
is an 11th grade subject.

01:05:29.484 --> 01:05:36.458
So I went into summer school
to do American history,

01:05:36.458 --> 01:05:40.094
to one of the high
schools in Des Moines.

01:05:40.094 --> 01:05:45.533
And then, in September, I
entered North High School

01:05:45.533 --> 01:05:54.142
and graduated in
end of May 1948.

01:05:54.142 --> 01:05:59.214
INT: Did your Holocaust
experience affect you at all

01:05:59.214 --> 01:06:04.085
in the way you interacted
with other American children

01:06:04.085 --> 01:06:05.887
when you arrived here?

01:06:05.887 --> 01:06:09.624
CB: Oh, I'm sure I did.

01:06:09.624 --> 01:06:13.528
First of all, it was very
hard for me to talk about it.

01:06:13.528 --> 01:06:14.696
Secondly, when I got--

01:06:14.696 --> 01:06:18.900
I got-- I was very fortunate
to have been able to go

01:06:18.900 --> 01:06:24.105
to college, to Grinnell
College, which is a very nice,

01:06:24.105 --> 01:06:27.642
private school in Iowa--

01:06:27.642 --> 01:06:30.979
a very fine private school.

01:06:30.979 --> 01:06:36.284
And I think that I was just
old beyond my years, you know?

01:06:36.284 --> 01:06:37.418
I worked very hard.

01:06:37.418 --> 01:06:39.220
I was on a
scholarship, but I had

01:06:39.220 --> 01:06:42.757
to support myself
for board and room

01:06:42.757 --> 01:06:45.693
by doing all kinds of jobs.

01:06:45.693 --> 01:06:47.261
And the thing that
bothered me most

01:06:47.261 --> 01:06:48.963
is that the young
people who were

01:06:48.963 --> 01:06:50.998
there who were given
the education really

01:06:50.998 --> 01:06:53.601
didn't appreciate it.

01:06:53.601 --> 01:06:56.771
But there was a function of the
fact that I had gone through

01:06:56.771 --> 01:06:58.973
things that they hadn't.

01:06:58.973 --> 01:07:02.543
And it took me about three years
to finding-- by my senior year,

01:07:02.543 --> 01:07:03.511
we were on a par.

01:07:03.511 --> 01:07:08.416
[LAUGHS] You know, they had
matured, and I had leveled off.

01:07:08.416 --> 01:07:11.786
So I think I enjoyed my
senior year the most.

01:07:11.786 --> 01:07:14.222
But th-- you know,
it was difficult

01:07:14.222 --> 01:07:19.293
for me to accept the fact that
they did not appreciate what,

01:07:19.293 --> 01:07:21.963
what they were given, you know?

01:07:21.963 --> 01:07:24.065
INT: Were you able to talk
about your experiences

01:07:24.065 --> 01:07:24.999
in the Holocaust to anyone?

01:07:24.999 --> 01:07:25.700
CB: Not really.

01:07:25.700 --> 01:07:26.434
Not really.

01:07:26.434 --> 01:07:28.903
I mean, it was--
it's very difficult--

01:07:28.903 --> 01:07:32.373
it was very difficult to
talk about it, because nobody

01:07:32.373 --> 01:07:33.875
could comprehend it.

01:07:33.875 --> 01:07:38.145
And I think that's why I said
Schindler's List, the film,

01:07:38.145 --> 01:07:40.915
it sort of opened up the
floodgates, because now

01:07:40.915 --> 01:07:46.287
people who see it are
able to ask questions,

01:07:46.287 --> 01:07:50.124
or at least comprehend
one's experience.

01:07:53.661 --> 01:07:58.332
INT: So after graduating
college, what did you do?

01:07:58.332 --> 01:08:01.302
CB: Well, I got
another fellowship.

01:08:01.302 --> 01:08:04.171
Well, I spent some-- one
summer at Northhampton School

01:08:04.171 --> 01:08:05.273
of Social Work--

01:08:05.273 --> 01:08:09.543
I mean at the Smith School of
Social Work in Northampton.

01:08:09.543 --> 01:08:11.512
And then I was fortunate.

01:08:11.512 --> 01:08:15.950
I had gotten a fellowship
to Columbia University.

01:08:15.950 --> 01:08:20.588
There were two of us who
won $10,000 scholarship

01:08:20.588 --> 01:08:25.259
for further study out of
something like 245 applicants.

01:08:25.259 --> 01:08:29.063
So that was quite a
feather in our cap.

01:08:29.063 --> 01:08:31.098
And I ended up at Columbia.

01:08:31.098 --> 01:08:35.136
And I got my master's
there in education,

01:08:35.136 --> 01:08:37.738
and lived at the
international house-- met

01:08:37.738 --> 01:08:39.040
my husband that way.

01:08:39.040 --> 01:08:40.541
INT: And what's
your husband's name?

01:08:40.541 --> 01:08:42.309
CB: Amir.

01:08:42.309 --> 01:08:46.047
And we got married in 1953.

01:08:46.047 --> 01:08:46.914
And then I continued.

01:08:46.914 --> 01:08:49.750
Oh, I had, you
know, beyond that--

01:08:49.750 --> 01:08:52.653
I went-- you know,
after that, we settled,

01:08:52.653 --> 01:08:56.323
and I continued my
education at the schools.

01:08:56.323 --> 01:09:00.261
And I ended up teaching
for about 25 years.

01:09:00.261 --> 01:09:01.529
INT: At what level?

01:09:01.529 --> 01:09:04.031
CB: I taught elementary school,
and I worked with youngsters

01:09:04.031 --> 01:09:07.001
who had learning difficulties.

01:09:07.001 --> 01:09:13.073
I felt that was the
right thing to do.

01:09:13.073 --> 01:09:15.643
I enjoyed it, too, very much.

01:09:15.643 --> 01:09:18.045
It was very gratifying.

01:09:18.045 --> 01:09:21.182
INT: And then you had
a family of your own?

01:09:21.182 --> 01:09:22.650
CB: Yes, two children.

01:09:22.650 --> 01:09:23.884
INT: And their names?

01:09:23.884 --> 01:09:26.554
CB: Robert is my son.

01:09:26.554 --> 01:09:31.025
And he's married to Lucy and
has a little girl named Rachel.

01:09:31.025 --> 01:09:32.726
She's four years old.

01:09:32.726 --> 01:09:34.461
And then I have a
daughter, Susan.

01:09:34.461 --> 01:09:37.431
And she's married to Bob.

01:09:37.431 --> 01:09:43.938
And they have a little boy named
Alex, Alexander and another one

01:09:43.938 --> 01:09:45.272
on the way.

01:09:45.272 --> 01:09:46.874
INT: Who's going
to have the baby?

01:09:46.874 --> 01:09:47.508
CB: Susan.

01:09:47.508 --> 01:09:48.309
INT: Your daughter.

01:09:48.309 --> 01:09:51.812
CB: My daughter, in March.

01:09:51.812 --> 01:09:52.780
INT: Tell me something.

01:09:52.780 --> 01:09:56.884
Do you feel that your Holocaust
experience influenced you

01:09:56.884 --> 01:09:59.219
in the way you raised
your own children?

01:09:59.219 --> 01:10:00.321
CB: Yes it did.

01:10:00.321 --> 01:10:01.021
INT: In what way?

01:10:01.021 --> 01:10:02.022
CB: Very much so.

01:10:02.022 --> 01:10:06.193
I didn't talk to them about it
till they-- till my son was 12

01:10:06.193 --> 01:10:07.628
and my daughter was 8.

01:10:07.628 --> 01:10:13.167
They had absolutely no idea
that I had been a camp survivor

01:10:13.167 --> 01:10:15.069
or had--

01:10:15.069 --> 01:10:17.137
I didn't want them to have--

01:10:17.137 --> 01:10:19.640
I didn't want them
to feel guilty.

01:10:19.640 --> 01:10:21.308
I wanted them to have
a happy childhood.

01:10:24.445 --> 01:10:27.948
I know other people talk
about it all the time.

01:10:27.948 --> 01:10:32.052
And, you know, different people
experience it differently.

01:10:32.052 --> 01:10:32.986
That was my way.

01:10:35.723 --> 01:10:38.692
I didn't want my
children to hate.

01:10:38.692 --> 01:10:40.961
And I think I achieved that.

01:10:40.961 --> 01:10:43.597
My daughter has been able
to go to Germany many times,

01:10:43.597 --> 01:10:46.900
and has friends in Germany,
has studied in Germany.

01:10:46.900 --> 01:10:50.471
And has not-- doesn't have the--

01:10:50.471 --> 01:10:56.977
didn't go there with,
with baggage, you know?

01:10:56.977 --> 01:11:01.548
She was able to meet people
and form her own opinions, not

01:11:01.548 --> 01:11:03.984
my opinions.

01:11:03.984 --> 01:11:06.887
And I think, you know--

01:11:06.887 --> 01:11:09.957
I think my living in
Germany did that for me.

01:11:09.957 --> 01:11:12.659
I think if I had come straight
from camp someplace else,

01:11:12.659 --> 01:11:15.128
I might have never been
able to work through this.

01:11:15.128 --> 01:11:17.931
But I did work through it,
and that was good for me.

01:11:20.634 --> 01:11:22.202
INT: Did you ever
have an occasion

01:11:22.202 --> 01:11:25.739
to see Oskar Schindler
after the war?

01:11:25.739 --> 01:11:27.374
CB: I didn't, but
my parents did.

01:11:27.374 --> 01:11:30.911
They met up with him
on a street in Munich

01:11:30.911 --> 01:11:34.047
just when we were waiting to--

01:11:34.047 --> 01:11:36.250
for our shipment--

01:11:36.250 --> 01:11:39.620
I mean, to Bremerhaven to
go to the United States.

01:11:39.620 --> 01:11:41.922
And from what I understand,
they chatted on the street.

01:11:41.922 --> 01:11:44.291
And he told them he was
particularly happy that we were

01:11:44.291 --> 01:11:45.425
going to the United States.

01:11:49.763 --> 01:11:51.932
I think if we had
lived in New York area,

01:11:51.932 --> 01:11:54.301
we might have met up with him.

01:11:54.301 --> 01:11:56.903
But because my parents
lived in Iowa--

01:11:56.903 --> 01:11:59.539
and he did come to
New York many times.

01:11:59.539 --> 01:12:02.809
And he did visit friends
of my parents, good friends

01:12:02.809 --> 01:12:04.711
of my parents--
the [? Rosners. ?]

01:12:04.711 --> 01:12:08.749
And had my parents
lived in New York area,

01:12:08.749 --> 01:12:11.952
they probably would
have met up with him.

01:12:11.952 --> 01:12:14.621
But Iowa was kind of far away.

01:12:17.424 --> 01:12:21.762
INT: Now that it's over
50 years after the war,

01:12:21.762 --> 01:12:23.196
is there any message
that you would

01:12:23.196 --> 01:12:25.298
like to leave for
future generations

01:12:25.298 --> 01:12:27.501
for your own children
and grandchildren?

01:12:27.501 --> 01:12:29.002
Ah.

01:12:29.002 --> 01:12:31.104
Don't hate.

01:12:31.104 --> 01:12:33.306
Try to live with your neighbor.

01:12:33.306 --> 01:12:36.042
Accept people for what they are.

01:12:36.042 --> 01:12:38.979
Everybody has
something to offer.

01:12:38.979 --> 01:12:40.947
Nobody's better
than anybody else.

01:12:40.947 --> 01:12:46.186
[PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] I
mean, those are my feelings.

01:12:46.186 --> 01:12:48.588
Try to see the good in people.

01:12:52.225 --> 01:12:54.161
Whether they can achieve
it, I don't know.

01:12:54.161 --> 01:12:59.032
But you know, that's,
that's the way.

01:12:59.032 --> 01:13:01.968
I mean, I hate to see what's
happening in places like Bosnia

01:13:01.968 --> 01:13:05.238
and Herzegovina, where you
have ethnic cleansing again,

01:13:05.238 --> 01:13:08.108
the same things
over and over again,

01:13:08.108 --> 01:13:10.744
the hatred that
goes on in Israel.

01:13:10.744 --> 01:13:14.247
I mean, these are
all human beings.

01:13:14.247 --> 01:13:18.318
They all eat the same way,
drink the same way, you know?

01:13:18.318 --> 01:13:21.154
They bleed the same way.

01:13:21.154 --> 01:13:28.295
So [PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS]
that's my message.

01:13:28.295 --> 01:13:29.329
INT: Thank you very much.

01:13:29.329 --> 01:13:29.663
CB: Thank you.

01:13:29.663 --> 01:13:31.331
INT: We appreciate
your taking the time

01:13:31.331 --> 01:13:33.800
to give us your testimony today.

01:13:33.800 --> 01:13:37.804
And now we'd like to meet the
other members of your family

01:13:37.804 --> 01:13:39.839
who are here, and look
at some of your pictures.

01:13:39.839 --> 01:13:40.340
CB: OK.

01:13:43.276 --> 01:13:46.346
INT: Mrs. Biniaz, would
you please introduce

01:13:46.346 --> 01:13:48.281
your lovely family to us?

01:13:48.281 --> 01:13:49.683
CB: I'll be delighted to.

01:13:49.683 --> 01:13:53.386
This is my mother, Phyllis
Karp, who is visiting here

01:13:53.386 --> 01:13:54.721
from Des Moines, Iowa.

01:13:54.721 --> 01:13:56.856
She's been here-- she
wants me to tell you--

01:13:56.856 --> 01:14:00.327
six weeks visiting in Camarillo.

01:14:00.327 --> 01:14:03.697
And this is my husband,
[? Bini. ?] We call him

01:14:03.697 --> 01:14:07.167
[? Bini ?] for short, but
actually his name is Amir,

01:14:07.167 --> 01:14:08.134
and he lives here.

01:14:08.134 --> 01:14:08.635
[LAUGHTER]

01:14:08.635 --> 01:14:10.970
INT: I hope so.

01:14:10.970 --> 01:14:14.774
Mrs. Karp, why don't
we start with you.

01:14:14.774 --> 01:14:16.576
Would you tell
me, please, do you

01:14:16.576 --> 01:14:21.514
think that your experience
in the Holocaust

01:14:21.514 --> 01:14:23.950
influenced you in the way
you raised your daughter?

01:14:27.053 --> 01:14:30.323
PHYLLIS KARP: You mean
after, after the war?

01:14:30.323 --> 01:14:34.160
Well, not really.

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:37.230
We raised her the
way, you know--

01:14:37.230 --> 01:14:40.300
we thought we did
the best, you know?

01:14:40.300 --> 01:14:44.671
But not influenced
by the Holocaust, no.

01:14:44.671 --> 01:14:50.844
We were very happy and
lucky to have her, you know?

01:14:50.844 --> 01:14:52.912
And we couldn't do enough.

01:14:52.912 --> 01:14:54.380
I mean, we didn't do so much.

01:14:54.380 --> 01:14:57.784
She did it all by herself.

01:14:57.784 --> 01:14:58.618
It's the truth.

01:15:01.921 --> 01:15:03.957
She was our pride and joy.

01:15:03.957 --> 01:15:08.428
[PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS]
I always say,

01:15:08.428 --> 01:15:11.998
we didn't have the quantity,
but we had the quality.

01:15:11.998 --> 01:15:14.701
CB: Aw.

01:15:14.701 --> 01:15:16.169
This is embarrassing.

01:15:16.169 --> 01:15:16.803
INT: This is a wonderful thing.

01:15:16.803 --> 01:15:17.904
PHYLLIS KARP: No it is not.

01:15:17.904 --> 01:15:20.373
It's the truth.

01:15:20.373 --> 01:15:22.008
Your father was so pr--

01:15:22.008 --> 01:15:24.477
he was so proud of
her, always talking

01:15:24.477 --> 01:15:27.480
about her accomplishments,
Phi Beta Kappa.

01:15:27.480 --> 01:15:33.920
I showed off because we had it
framed in our second bedroom.

01:15:33.920 --> 01:15:36.522
And every time he was
proud-- if somebody

01:15:36.522 --> 01:15:41.027
came to visit us, you
know, to show how proud,

01:15:41.027 --> 01:15:47.033
how smart his daughter is.

01:15:47.033 --> 01:15:48.868
INT: And Bini--

01:15:48.868 --> 01:15:49.836
AMIR BINIAZ: That's me.

01:15:49.836 --> 01:15:52.672
INT: Why don't you tell us a few
things about your lovely wife.

01:15:52.672 --> 01:15:55.975
What have you got to
add to this testimony?

01:15:55.975 --> 01:15:58.978
AMIR BINIAZ: I think my
mother-in-law was very eloquent

01:15:58.978 --> 01:15:59.479
about it.

01:15:59.479 --> 01:16:02.682
I think Celina is probably
one of the smartest

01:16:02.682 --> 01:16:07.053
ladies I've, I've known-- one
of the smartest people I know.

01:16:07.053 --> 01:16:09.155
And she's a great mother.

01:16:09.155 --> 01:16:10.289
She's very caring.

01:16:10.289 --> 01:16:12.425
She's a caregiver.

01:16:12.425 --> 01:16:16.729
And I'm, just as equally
as my mother-in-law,

01:16:16.729 --> 01:16:20.466
proud to have her in the family.

01:16:20.466 --> 01:16:23.369
INT: And how long have
you been married now?

01:16:23.369 --> 01:16:25.538
AMIR BINIAZ: I think you'd
better help me with that.

01:16:25.538 --> 01:16:26.038
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:26.038 --> 01:16:29.175
CB: 42 Years.

01:16:29.175 --> 01:16:30.309
INT: Thank you very much.

01:16:30.309 --> 01:16:33.146
We appreciate your taking
the time to be with us today.

01:16:33.146 --> 01:16:34.580
PHYLLIS KARP: May
I add something?

01:16:34.580 --> 01:16:35.548
INT: Yes, please.

01:16:35.548 --> 01:16:37.183
PHYLLIS KARP: You
know, my husband

01:16:37.183 --> 01:16:40.553
was sick for awhile,
two and a half years.

01:16:40.553 --> 01:16:43.356
And she was just wonderful--

01:16:43.356 --> 01:16:46.792
leaving her husband alone
here, and coming to Des Moines

01:16:46.792 --> 01:16:48.561
to stay to help me out.

01:16:48.561 --> 01:16:52.265
You know, it's something--

01:16:52.265 --> 01:16:53.833
you cannot buy it.

01:16:53.833 --> 01:16:56.569
CB: That's what every
daughter should do.

01:16:56.569 --> 01:16:57.770
PHYLLIS KARP: But they don't.

01:16:57.770 --> 01:16:58.171
CB: Well--

01:16:58.171 --> 01:16:59.138
PHYLLIS KARP: You are--

01:16:59.138 --> 01:17:01.674
you're exceptional.

01:17:01.674 --> 01:17:04.043
It's true.

01:17:04.043 --> 01:17:05.978
INT: Well thank you very much.

01:17:05.978 --> 01:17:07.880
We appreciate your time.

01:17:07.880 --> 01:17:10.449
And now we're going to take a
look at some of your pictures.

01:17:10.449 --> 01:17:10.950
CB: OK.

01:17:16.022 --> 01:17:21.661
This is a picture of my mother,
Phyllis, and myself as a baby.

01:17:21.661 --> 01:17:26.599
It was taken in 1931
in Krakow, in Poland.

01:17:29.235 --> 01:17:31.904
I must be about--

01:17:31.904 --> 01:17:35.408
probably five or six
months old on that picture.

01:17:35.408 --> 01:17:37.877
INT: Where did you
get this picture from?

01:17:37.877 --> 01:17:42.481
CB: Well, it was probably
sent to one of our relatives,

01:17:42.481 --> 01:17:44.317
either in the United
States or in Israel,

01:17:44.317 --> 01:17:47.953
because we had none
of the pictures left.

01:17:47.953 --> 01:17:50.589
Whatever pictures we
see today are pictures

01:17:50.589 --> 01:17:53.826
that have been preserved
by family members,

01:17:53.826 --> 01:17:55.661
and then given to
us after the war.

01:18:00.833 --> 01:18:04.637
That is a picture of
my mother and myself.

01:18:04.637 --> 01:18:07.139
I am about two years old
there-- less probably,

01:18:07.139 --> 01:18:08.641
a year and a half or two--

01:18:08.641 --> 01:18:14.680
on a street in Krakow, Poland,
probably taken in 1933.

01:18:14.680 --> 01:18:16.348
INT: And give us the
name of your mother

01:18:16.348 --> 01:18:17.783
and yourself again, please.

01:18:17.783 --> 01:18:18.918
CB: My name is Celina.

01:18:18.918 --> 01:18:24.990
And my mother's name in Poland
was Felicia, Fela, Felicia.

01:18:24.990 --> 01:18:26.826
And we went by the name of Karp.

01:18:33.466 --> 01:18:39.205
That is a picture of me, Celina,
on my first day of school,

01:18:39.205 --> 01:18:41.307
dressed in a uniform.

01:18:41.307 --> 01:18:44.944
I am six years
old, and I'm going

01:18:44.944 --> 01:18:49.715
to the public school called
Adam Mickiewicz, named

01:18:49.715 --> 01:18:53.085
for the Polish poet.

01:18:53.085 --> 01:18:57.556
It is taken in the courtyard
of our apartment building

01:18:57.556 --> 01:19:03.395
at 22 [POLISH] in
Krakow, Poland.

01:19:03.395 --> 01:19:08.434
And the year would have
to be, then, 1937--

01:19:08.434 --> 01:19:17.543
September of 1937.

01:19:17.543 --> 01:19:23.849
This picture was taken
on the ship, SS Marl--

01:19:23.849 --> 01:19:25.851
Marlin.

01:19:25.851 --> 01:19:29.855
And it is taking
us from Bremerhaven

01:19:29.855 --> 01:19:32.124
to the United States.

01:19:32.124 --> 01:19:37.296
It is my birthday,
28th of May, 1947.

01:19:37.296 --> 01:19:41.600
On the left hand side is
my mother, Phyllis Karp,

01:19:41.600 --> 01:19:44.703
or at that time,
still Felicia Karp.

01:19:44.703 --> 01:19:50.175
Right next to her is a picture
of myself, Celina Karp.

01:19:50.175 --> 01:19:52.678
I don't know who the other two
people are on the right hand

01:19:52.678 --> 01:19:53.812
side.

01:19:53.812 --> 01:19:57.683
But looking through the opening
on the right hand side, where

01:19:57.683 --> 01:20:01.086
the people are standing,
to the very back there,

01:20:01.086 --> 01:20:04.723
you see Europe disappearing
on the horizon.

01:20:04.723 --> 01:20:07.426
We were just leaving on
the ship from Bremerhaven.

01:20:12.865 --> 01:20:18.737
This is my concentration
camp number, 76318.

01:20:18.737 --> 01:20:23.041
The KZ stands for
Konzentrationslager Auschwitz.

01:20:23.041 --> 01:20:25.677
Since we were the
300 women who did not

01:20:25.677 --> 01:20:29.381
get tattooed in Auschwitz,
we received these numbers

01:20:29.381 --> 01:20:31.150
to wear on our uniforms.

01:20:33.952 --> 01:20:36.221
INT: What does the red
triangle stand for?

01:20:36.221 --> 01:20:36.955
Do you know?

01:20:36.955 --> 01:20:37.456
CB: Jew.

01:20:40.893 --> 01:20:42.628
INT: That's how they
designated the Jews,

01:20:42.628 --> 01:20:43.729
with the red triangle?

01:20:43.729 --> 01:20:47.766
CB: Either with a star of
David, a yellow Star of David,

01:20:47.766 --> 01:20:50.569
or the red triangle.

01:20:53.972 --> 01:20:57.242
Actually, the red triangle
also meant prisoner, you know?

01:21:01.213 --> 01:21:04.683
In 1948, I attended
the Encampment

01:21:04.683 --> 01:21:07.853
for Citizenship, which was
sponsored by the Ethical

01:21:07.853 --> 01:21:11.723
Culture Society of New York.

01:21:11.723 --> 01:21:14.493
The encampment took
place at Fieldston School

01:21:14.493 --> 01:21:16.428
in New York City.

01:21:16.428 --> 01:21:18.530
Mrs. Roosevelt, Mrs.
Eleanor Roosevelt,

01:21:18.530 --> 01:21:23.702
was a sponsor of the encampment,
and we would go to her estate

01:21:23.702 --> 01:21:27.572
in Hyde Park for a
picnic on the lawn.

01:21:27.572 --> 01:21:31.243
I took this picture of her
while she was talking to us

01:21:31.243 --> 01:21:33.545
with a little Brownie camera.

01:21:33.545 --> 01:21:37.482
She was a wonderful lady, as
you can see that in her face,

01:21:37.482 --> 01:21:39.151
and in her smile.

01:21:39.151 --> 01:21:41.853
She was very interested
in the young people,

01:21:41.853 --> 01:21:45.190
and in the experiment
in living together

01:21:45.190 --> 01:21:46.825
of various races and religions.

01:21:52.731 --> 01:21:55.367
This is a picture of me, Celina.

01:21:55.367 --> 01:21:57.235
I'm 16 years old.

01:21:57.235 --> 01:22:01.039
This is 1947, in July--

01:22:01.039 --> 01:22:03.842
my first summer in
the United States.

01:22:03.842 --> 01:22:06.144
This picture was taken
at my uncle's house

01:22:06.144 --> 01:22:07.212
in Des Moines, Iowa.

01:22:09.915 --> 01:22:10.782
I was a teenager.

01:22:10.782 --> 01:22:15.053
[LAUGHS]

01:22:15.053 --> 01:22:18.957
In 1993, the film
Schindler's List

01:22:18.957 --> 01:22:21.693
was produced and
opened to various--

01:22:21.693 --> 01:22:23.228
in various theaters.

01:22:23.228 --> 01:22:26.631
This is a picture of my mother,
Phyllis Karp, my father,

01:22:26.631 --> 01:22:28.266
Irvin Karp.

01:22:28.266 --> 01:22:30.769
And the little pot my
mother is holding--

01:22:30.769 --> 01:22:32.404
the little red pot--

01:22:32.404 --> 01:22:36.675
is the pot we received
at Schindler's factory

01:22:36.675 --> 01:22:39.411
from which we drank
our hot liquids.

01:22:39.411 --> 01:22:43.448
My mother has kept it all these
years as a reminder of what

01:22:43.448 --> 01:22:45.016
it was like to be in a camp.

01:22:48.053 --> 01:22:49.521
INT: Where was
this picture taken?

01:22:49.521 --> 01:22:52.324
CB: The picture was taken in by
the Des Moines Register people

01:22:52.324 --> 01:22:59.798
in Des Moines, Iowa, in 1993.

01:22:59.798 --> 01:23:05.704
This picture was taken
in 1989 at Yad Vashem

01:23:05.704 --> 01:23:09.908
on the Allee of the Righteous
in front of Schindler's tree.

01:23:09.908 --> 01:23:12.978
On the right hand side is
my mother, Phyllis Karp.

01:23:12.978 --> 01:23:16.147
Next to her is my
father, Irvin Karp.

01:23:16.147 --> 01:23:18.984
And I am on the left,
Celina Karp Biniaz.

01:23:31.763 --> 01:23:32.297
OK.

01:23:32.297 --> 01:23:37.001
This picture was taken at 1582
Calle Aurora in Camarillo,

01:23:37.001 --> 01:23:44.743
California on December 1994.

01:23:44.743 --> 01:23:48.480
And the people in the picture
are, on the left, myself.

01:23:48.480 --> 01:23:52.217
Next to me is my
son-in-law, Bob Harris,

01:23:52.217 --> 01:23:56.554
holding up my grandson,
Alexander Biniaz Harris.

01:23:56.554 --> 01:24:00.692
Next to Alexander is my
daughter, Susan Biniaz.

01:24:00.692 --> 01:24:04.028
Below is my husband,
Amir Biniaz.

01:24:04.028 --> 01:24:10.702
Next to him is my granddaughter,
Rachel Hood Biniaz Next to her

01:24:10.702 --> 01:24:13.404
is her mother, Lucy Hood.

01:24:13.404 --> 01:24:17.942
And next to her is
my son, Robert Biniaz

01:24:17.942 --> 01:24:19.344
We're a happy family.

01:24:24.782 --> 01:24:28.253
Since I'm a survivor
of Schindler's List,

01:24:28.253 --> 01:24:31.422
I was invited to the
preview of the film.

01:24:31.422 --> 01:24:34.859
My husband took this picture
in front of the poster

01:24:34.859 --> 01:24:37.262
advertising Schindler's List.

01:24:37.262 --> 01:24:40.331
This was the first
time I saw the film.

01:24:40.331 --> 01:24:43.902
I was incredibly moved by it,
as was the entire theater.

01:24:43.902 --> 01:24:50.842
There wasn't a sound
emanating from anybody even

01:24:50.842 --> 01:24:54.379
after the end of the film,
except some people were crying.

01:24:54.379 --> 01:24:57.949
I think the film was
exceptionally well done.

01:24:57.949 --> 01:25:02.053
I think Mr. Spielberg did
an excellent job with a very

01:25:02.053 --> 01:25:06.958
difficult
[PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] job--

01:25:06.958 --> 01:25:08.860
a very difficult topic.

01:25:08.860 --> 01:25:14.966
[PAUSES FOR 5 SECONDS]
And I think

01:25:14.966 --> 01:25:19.337
he sort of opened up people's
eyes and ears to what

01:25:19.337 --> 01:25:22.173
was happening at
the time, and has

01:25:22.173 --> 01:25:23.875
made it possible
for a lot of people

01:25:23.875 --> 01:25:27.278
that come forth and speak
about their experiences.

01:25:27.278 --> 01:25:32.583
I know I did not speak about my
experiences for over 45 years.

01:25:32.583 --> 01:25:36.788
And it was only after
the Schindler's List film

01:25:36.788 --> 01:25:41.025
was shown to people that I
started talking about it.

01:25:41.025 --> 01:25:45.563
So I think even for me, Mr.
Spielberg made it happen.

01:25:45.563 --> 01:25:49.033
And I hope he's made it
happen for a lot of people.

01:25:49.033 --> 01:25:50.101
Thank you.

01:25:50.101 --> 01:25:52.437
INT: Thank you very much.

